ainment outlets, nightclubs and tuition centres, and restricting remaining building crowd density such as MRT and LRT stations, and shopping centres to one person per 16 square metres of space, failing which they will be asked to close. \n* 3 January - \n**An appeal by States Times Review to cancel the correction notices is rejected.<ref name=\"STR\">{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/states-times-reviews-application-to-cancel-pofma-order-rejected-sdp-files-separate |title=States Times Review's application to cancel Pofma order rejected; SDP files separate application |date=3 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Singapore Democratic Party]] appeals to cancel the correction notices issued the previous month,<ref name=\"STR\"/> coming a day after it defended its posts.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/fake-news-law-sdp-defends-posts-says-it-will-apply-to-cancel-corrections-on-jan-3 |title=Fake news law: SDP defends posts, says it will apply to cancel correction notices; MOM says party should follow process |date=2 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> The request is rejected three days later.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Yuen |first1=Sin |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/singapolitics/josephine-teo-rejects-sdps-bid-to-cancel-correction-notices |title=SDP's bid to get correction order cancelled rejected |date=6 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 4 January - The [[Sembawang Hot Spring Park]] reopens with refreshed facilities, the only natural hot spring in Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Mohan |first1=Matthew |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/sembawang-hot-spring-park-reopens-cascading-pool-floral-walk-12232820 |title=Sembawang Hot Spring Park reopens with cascading pool, cafe and floral walk |website=CNA |access-date=4 January 2020 |date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 6 January - [[Eunoia Junior College]] moves to its new campus in Bishan, making it Singapore's first high-rise Junior College. It is also integrated with the future Bishan North Community Club.<ref>{{cite web |title=Classes to begin at Singapore's first high-rise junior college on Jan 6 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/classes-to-begin-at-singapores-first-high-rise-junior-college-on-jan-6 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 January 2020 |date=2 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Menon |first1=Malavika |title=Eunoia Junior College moves in to new Bishan campus |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/education/eunoia-junior-college-moves-in-to-new-campus-in-sin-ming-avenue |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 January 2020 |date=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 8 January - The Singapore Democratic Party (SDP) appeals the correction in court, the first such court challenge.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Yuen |first1=Sin |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/singapolitics/sdp-appeals-against-correction-notices-by-manpower-ministry-first-court |title=SDP appeals against correction notices by Manpower Ministry in first court challenge of fake news law |date=8 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> The SDP requests to have the case held in open court due to public interest,<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/case-against-pofma-corrections-should-be-heard-in-open-court-sdp |title=Case against Pofma corrections should be heard in open court: SDP |date=13 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> which is subsequently rejected in view of rules.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/high-court-rejects-sdps-application-to-have-pofma-case-heard-in-open-court |title=High Court rejects SDP's application to have Pofma case heard in open court |date=16 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> After the hearing, the Attorney-General's Chambers (AGC) said that SDP made misleading statements,<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/pofma-challenge-agc-seeks-further-hearing-says-sdp-mischaracterised-its-arguments |title=Pofma challenge: AGC seeks further hearing, says SDP mischaracterised its arguments |date=20 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> which the SDP promised to correct later on.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tee |first1=Zhuo |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/sdp-promises-to-correct-article-that-mis-characterises-agcs-position |title=SDP promises to correct article that mischaracterises AGC's position: AGC |date=23 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 22 January - [[Lawyers for Liberty]] (LFL) and three parties who shared LFL's posts are issued correction notices against false allegations on the [[death penalty]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/mha-refutes-malaysia-ngos-allegations-against-spores-execution-method-to |title=MHA refutes Malaysia NGO's claims against S'pore's execution method, issues Pofma correction orders against parties |date=22 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> All parties complied except for LFL, causing the [[Info-communications Media Development Authority|Infocomm Media Development Authority]] to block LFL website the following day.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tee |first1=Zhuo |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/imda-to-block-malaysian-ngo-website-after-it-fails-to-comply-with-pofma-correction-mci |title=IMDA to block Malaysian NGO website after it fails to comply with Pofma correction: MCI |date=23 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> LFL has since filed a court case in Malaysia.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=H. Rodzi |first1=Nadirah |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/malaysian-rights-group-sues-minister-k-shanmugam-in-kl-over-pofma-correction-order |title=Malaysian rights group sues Minister K Shanmugam in KL over Pofma correction order |date=24 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> [[The Online Citizen]] appealed the order, which is rejected on 24 January.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/home-affairs-minister-rejects-tocs-application-to-cancel-pofma-correction-order |title=Home Affairs Minister Shanmugam rejects TOC's application to cancel Pofma correction order |date=24 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 30 January - [[Mediacorp]] renames its digital media platforms Toggle, MeRadio and MeClub to [[meWatch]], meListen and meRewards respectively.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mediacorp rolls out meWATCH, meLISTEN, meREWARDS and meCONNECT |url=https://www.mediacorp.sg/en/mediacorp-in-the-news/media-releases/mediacorp-rolls-out-mewatch-melisten-merewards-and-meconnect-12369778 |website=Mediacorp |accessdate=30 January 2020 |date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 31 January - \n**The first stage of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line]] (spanning from [[Woodlands North MRT station|Woodlands North]] to [[Woodlands South MRT station|Woodlands South]]) opens.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Vanessa |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/first-three-stations-of-thomson-east-coast-line-to-begin-service-on-jan-31-free |title=First three stations of Thomson-East Coast Line to begin service on Jan 31; free travel for commuters for three days |website=The Straits Times |access-date=11 December 2019 |date=11 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Kai Yi |title=3 stations on Thomson-East Coast Line begin operations |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/3-stations-on-thomson-east-coast-line-begin-operations |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=15 January 2020 |date=31 January 2020}}</ref> In addition, a new MRT map is rolled out at all stations with the [[Circle MRT line]] as a focus.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/new-mrt-network-map-be-rolled-out-all-stations-jan-31 |title=New MRT network map to be rolled out at all stations by Jan 31 |website=Today |access-date=11 December 2019 |date=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n**[[Cold Stone Creamery]] closes after being in Singapore for 10 years.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Quek |first1=Eunice |title=Cold Stone Creamery exits Singapore on Jan 31 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/food/cold-stone-creamery-exits-singapore-on-jan-31 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=15 January 2020 |date=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n* 5 February - The Singapore Democratic Party lost the appeal, with the court ruling that a statement has to be proven false by the Government after a correction is issued.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tham |first1=Yuen-C |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/first-court-challenge-against-fake-news-law-fails-high-court-dismisses-sdps-appeal |title=First court challenge against fake news law fails; High Court dismisses SDP's appeal |date=5 February 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n* 10 March - An extension of the [[Cross Island MRT line]] is announced. Spanning {{Convert|7.3|km|miles|abbr=in}} from [[Pasir Ris MRT station|Pasir Ris]] to [[Punggol MRT/LRT station|Punggol]], the four-station extension will be completed by 2031.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Kai Yi |title=Punggol residents to get four more train stations by 2031 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/punggol-residents-to-get-four-more-train-stations-by-2031 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=10 March 2020 |date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/punggol-extension-cross-island-line-mrt-stations-construction-12521038|title=Punggol extension on Cross Island Line to begin construction in 2022|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310042859/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/punggol-extension-cross-island-line-mrt-stations-construction-12521038| archive-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 13 March - [[2020 Singaporean general election|General Elections]]: The [[List of Singaporean electoral divisions|Electoral Boundaries Review Committee report]] is released. The 14th parliament will consist of 93 members from 31 constituencies (14 Single Member Constituencies and 17 Group Representation Constituencies), up from 89 seats from the current 29 constituencies. In addition, six-member GRCs will be abolished, with the maximum being five MPs in each GRC.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Sim |first1=Royston |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/singapore-ge-new-electoral-boundaries-announced-14-smcs-17-grcs-in-next-election |title=Singapore GE: New electoral boundaries announced; 14 SMCs, 17 GRCs in next election |website=The Straits Times |access-date=13 March 2020 |date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/general-election-ebrc-electoral-boundaries-grc-smc-12535200|title=More electoral divisions, no 6-member GRCs in coming election: EBRC report|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020|date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 31 March - [[Liang Court]], a shopping mall in [[Clarke Quay]], ceases operation.\n\n===Predicted and scheduled events===\n* 9 June - [[Lotte Corporation|Lotte Duty Free]] will take over [[DFS Group]]'s [[Changi Airport]] liquor and tobacco stores<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ang |first1=Prisca |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/lotte-duty-free-to-take-over-dfs-liquor-and-tobacco-stores-in-changi-airport-from-june |title=Lotte Duty Free to take over DFS liquor and tobacco stores in Changi Airport from June 2020 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=25 October 2019 |date=24 October 2019}}</ref> as the latter ends its 39-year tenancy due to a challenging environment.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Heng |first1=Melissa |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/dfs-pulls-out-of-changi-airports-liquor-tobacco-business-all-stores-to-shut-in |title=DFS stores in Changi Airport to close in June 2020; South Korea's Shilla and Lotte among 3 new bidders |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=25 October 2019 |date=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n* Kallang Polyclinic, connected to Kwong Wai Shiu Hospital will open.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Baharudin |first1=Hariz |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/kwong-wai-shiu-hospital-nursing-home-opens-after-100m-facelift |title=Kwong Wai Shiu Hospital nursing home opens after $96m facelift |website=The Straits Times |access-date=7 July 2019 |date=6 October 2018}}</ref> \n* The second stage of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line]] (spanning from [[Springleaf MRT station|Springleaf]] to [[Caldecott MRT station|Caldecott]]) will open.\n*[[2020 Singaporean general election]]\n\n==Deaths==\n* 1 January - [[Ng Jui Ping]], former [[Chief of Defence Force (Singapore)|Chief of Defence Force]] (b. 1948).<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapores-second-chief-of-defence-force-ng-jui-ping-dies-at-71|title = Singapore's second Chief of Defence Force Ng Jui Ping dies at 71|work = [[The Straits Times]]|date = 1 January 2020|accessdate = 1 January 2020|last = Menon|first = Malavika}}</ref>\n* 9 January -\n**[[Jo Heng]], lyricist (b. 1960).<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Ang |first1=Benson |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/xinyao-lyricist-jo-heng-who-wrote-lyrics-for-singers-like-jacky-cheung-and |title=Xinyao lyricist Jo Heng, who wrote lyrics for singers like Jacky Cheung and Eric Moo, dies at 59 |date=9 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Yong Pung How]] - 2nd [[Chief Justice of Singapore]] (b. 1926).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |title=Singapore's former chief justice Yong Pung How dies, aged 93 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/former-chief-justice-yong-pung-how-dies-he-was-93 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=9 January 2019 |date=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Singapore}}\n{{Year in Asia |2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2020s in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2020 in Asia|Singapore]]\n[[Category:2020 by country|Singapore]]\n", "name_user": "TheGreatSG'rean", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor changes.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_in_Singapore"}
{"title_page": "Promising Young Woman", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Promising Young Woman\n| image          = Promising Young Woman.jpeg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster \n| director       = [[Emerald Fennell]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Ben Browning\n* Emerald Fennell\n* [[Margot Robbie]]\n* Tom Ackerley\n* Josey McNamara\n* Ashley Fox\n}}\n| writer         = Emerald Fennell\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Carey Mulligan]]\n* [[Bo Burnham]]\n* [[Alison Brie]]\n* [[Clancy Brown]]\n* [[Jennifer Coolidge]]\n* [[Connie Britton]]\n* [[Laverne Cox]]\n}}<!--per poster billing block-->\n| music          = Anthony Willis\n| cinematography = Benjamin Kracun\n| editing        = Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Thoraval\n| production companies         = {{Plainlist|\n{{nowrap|[[LuckyChap Entertainment]]}}\n* [[FilmNation Entertainment]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Focus Features]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|1|25|[[Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]]}}\n| runtime        = 113 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sundance.org/projects/promising-young-woman|title=Promising Young Woman|website=[[Sundance Film Festival]]|accessdate=December 11, 2019}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Promising Young Woman''''' is a 2020 American [[black comedy|black]] [[comedy-drama]] film written, directed and co-produced by [[Emerald Fennell]] (in her feature film directorial debut). It stars [[Carey Mulligan]], [[Bo Burnham]], [[Alison Brie]], [[Clancy Brown]], [[Jennifer Coolidge]], [[Connie Britton]] and [[Laverne Cox]].\n\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] on January 25, 2020.\n\n== Plot ==\nEveryone said Cassie (Carey Mulligan) was a promising young woman, until a mysterious event abruptly derailed her future. But nothing in Cassie's life is what it appears to be: she's wickedly smart, tantalizingly cunning, and she is living a secret double life by night. Now, an unexpected encounter is about to give Cassie a chance to right the wrongs of the past.<ref>https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/promising-young-woman-trailer-carey-mulligan-killing-eve-1202196229/</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Carey Mulligan]] as Cassandra \u201cCassie\u201d Thomas\n* [[Bo Burnham]] as Ryan\n* [[Alison Brie]] as Madison\n* [[Clancy Brown]] as Stanley Thomas\n* [[Jennifer Coolidge]] as Susan\n* [[Connie Britton]] as Dean Walker\n* [[Laverne Cox]] as Gail\n* [[Adam Brody]] as Jez\n* [[Max Greenfield]] as Joe\n* [[Christopher Mintz-Plasse]] as Neil\n* [[Sam Richardson (actor)|Sam Richardson]] as Paul\n* [[Molly Shannon]] as Mrs. Fisher\n* [[Alfred Molina]] as Jordan\n* Angela Zhou as Todd\n* [[Chris Lowell]] as Al Monroe\n\n==Production==\nIn January 2019, it was announced [[Carey Mulligan]] had joined the cast of the film, with [[Emerald Fennell]] directing from a screenplay she wrote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/carey-mulligan-promising-young-woman-filmnation-killing-eve-1202546476/|title=Carey Mulligan To Star In FilmNation, LuckyChap Thriller 'Promising Young Woman' \u2014 EFM|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Andreas|last=Wiseman|date=January 31, 2019|accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> In March 2019, [[Bo Burnham]], [[Alison Brie]], [[Connie Britton]], [[Adam Brody]], [[Jennifer Coolidge]], [[Laverne Cox]], [[Max Greenfield]], [[Christopher Mintz-Plasse]], [[Sam Richardson (actor)|Sam Richardson]] and [[Molly Shannon]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/bo-burnham-alison-brie-connie-britton-adam-brody-carey-mulligan-promising-young-woman-cast-1202585238/|title=Bo Burnham To Star Opposite Carey Mulligan In 'Promising Young Woman'; Alison Brie, Connie Britton, Adam Brody & More Round Cast|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=March 29, 2019|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> In April 2019, Angela Zhou and [[Clancy Brown]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/hell-on-wheels-angela-zhou-promising-young-woman-ron-funches-sylvie-1202586909/|title='Hell on Wheels' Star Angela Zhou Joins 'Promising Young Woman'; Ron Funches Cast In 'Sylvie'|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=April 2, 2019|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/clancy-brown-promising-young-woman-focus-features-1202591523/|title=Clancy Brown Boards 'Promising Young Woman' At Focus Features|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=April 8, 2019|accessdate=April 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] began on March 26, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/emeraldfennell/status/1110541220479066112|title=Day 1 of \"Promising Young Woman\"!!!|website=[[Twitter.com]]|first=Emerald|last=Fennell|date=March 26, 2019|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn February 2019, [[Focus Features]] acquired distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/carey-mulligan-focus-filmnation-luckychap-sets-promising-young-woman-1202556617/|title=Focus Boards Carey Mulligan Thriller 'Promising Young Woman'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Mike|last=Fleming Jr|date=February 13, 2019|accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> It had its world premiere at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] on January 25, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sundance-2020-unveils-female-powered-lineup-taylor-swift-gloria-steinem-films-1259538?|title=Sundance Unveils Female-Powered Lineup Featuring Taylor Swift, Gloria Steinem, Abortion Road Trip Drama|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Tatiana|last=Siegel|date=December 4, 2019|accessdate=December 4, 2019}}</ref> It was scheduled to be released on April 17, 2020,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Focus-Features-to-Release-PROMISING-YOUNG-WOMAN-on-April-17-20191122|title=Focus Features to Release PROMISING YOUNG WOMAN on April 17|website=Broadway World|date=November 22, 2019|accessdate=December 3, 2019}}</ref> however due to the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]] it was pulled from the schedule.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.focusfeatures.com/promising-young-woman|title=Promising Young Woman|website=Focus Features|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical reception ===\nOn [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 93% based on 46 reviews, and an [[average rating]] of 7.54/10. The site's critics consensus reads: \"A boldly provocative, timely thriller, ''Promising Young Woman'' is an auspicious feature debut for writer-director Emerald Fennell -- and a career highlight for Carey Mulligan.\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Promising Young Woman (2020)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/promising_young_woman|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 74 out of 100, based on 14 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Promising Young Woman Reviews|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/promising-young-woman|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDB title|9620292}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:2020s feminist films]]\n[[Category:2020s thriller films]]\n[[Category:2020s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:2020s vigilante films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American feminist films]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American vigilante films]]\n[[Category:2020 directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:FilmNation Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Margot Robbie]]\n[[Category:Focus Features films]]\n[[Category:LuckyChap Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Rape and revenge films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Promising Young Woman\n| image          = Promising Young Woman.jpeg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster \n| director       = [[Emerald Fennell]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Ben Browning\n* Emerald Fennell\n* [[Margot Robbie]]\n* Tom Ackerley\n* Josey McNamara\n* Ashley Fox\n}}\n| writer         = Emerald Fennell\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Carey Mulligan]]\n* [[Bo Burnham]]\n* [[Alison Brie]]\n* [[Clancy Brown]]\n* [[Jennifer Coolidge]]\n* [[Connie Britton]]\n* [[Laverne Cox]]\n}}<!--per poster billing block-->\n| music          = Anthony Willis\n| cinematography = Benjamin Kracun\n| editing        = Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Thoraval\n| production companies         = {{Plainlist|\n{{nowrap|[[LuckyChap Entertainment]]}}\n* [[FilmNation Entertainment]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Focus Features]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|1|25|[[Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]]}}\n| runtime        = 113 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sundance.org/projects/promising-young-woman|title=Promising Young Woman|website=[[Sundance Film Festival]]|accessdate=December 11, 2019}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Promising Young Woman''''' is a 2020 American [[black comedy|black]] [[comedy-drama]] film written, directed and co-produced by [[Emerald Fennell]] (in her feature film directorial debut). It stars [[Carey Mulligan]], [[Bo Burnham]], [[Alison Brie]], [[Clancy Brown]], [[Jennifer Coolidge]], [[Connie Britton]] and [[Laverne Cox]].\n\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] on January 25, 2020.\n\n== Plot ==\nEveryone said Cassie (Carey Mulligan) was a promising young woman, until a mysterious event abruptly derailed her future. But nothing in Cassie's life is what it appears to be: she's wickedly smart, tantalizingly cunning, and she is living a secret double life by night. Now, an unexpected encounter is about to give Cassie a chance to right the wrongs of the past.<ref>https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/promising-young-woman-trailer-carey-mulligan-killing-eve-1202196229/</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Carey Mulligan]] as Cassandra \u201cCassie\u201d Thomas\n* [[Bo Burnham]] as Ryan\n* [[Alison Brie]] as Madison\n* [[Clancy Brown]] as Stanley Thomas\n* [[Jennifer Coolidge]] as Susan\n* [[Connie Britton]] as Dean Walker\n* [[Laverne Cox]] as Gail\n* [[Adam Brody]] as Jez\n* [[Max Greenfield]] as Joe\n* [[Christopher Mintz-Plasse]] as Neil\n* [[Sam Richardson (actor)|Sam Richardson]] as Paul\n* [[Molly Shannon]] as Mrs. Fisher\n* [[Alfred Molina]] as Jordan\n* Angela Zhou as Todd\n* [[Chris Lowell]] as Al Monroe\n\n==Production==\nIn January 2019, it was announced [[Carey Mulligan]] had joined the cast of the film, with [[Emerald Fennell]] directing from a screenplay she wrote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/carey-mulligan-promising-young-woman-filmnation-killing-eve-1202546476/|title=Carey Mulligan To Star In FilmNation, LuckyChap Thriller 'Promising Young Woman' \u2014 EFM|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Andreas|last=Wiseman|date=January 31, 2019|accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> In March 2019, [[Bo Burnham]], [[Alison Brie]], [[Connie Britton]], [[Adam Brody]], [[Jennifer Coolidge]], [[Laverne Cox]], [[Max Greenfield]], [[Christopher Mintz-Plasse]], [[Sam Richardson (actor)|Sam Richardson]] and [[Molly Shannon]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/bo-burnham-alison-brie-connie-britton-adam-brody-carey-mulligan-promising-young-woman-cast-1202585238/|title=Bo Burnham To Star Opposite Carey Mulligan In 'Promising Young Woman'; Alison Brie, Connie Britton, Adam Brody & More Round Cast|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=March 29, 2019|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> In April 2019, Angela Zhou and [[Clancy Brown]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/hell-on-wheels-angela-zhou-promising-young-woman-ron-funches-sylvie-1202586909/|title='Hell on Wheels' Star Angela Zhou Joins 'Promising Young Woman'; Ron Funches Cast In 'Sylvie'|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=April 2, 2019|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/clancy-brown-promising-young-woman-focus-features-1202591523/|title=Clancy Brown Boards 'Promising Young Woman' At Focus Features|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=April 8, 2019|accessdate=April 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] began on March 26, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/emeraldfennell/status/1110541220479066112|title=Day 1 of \"Promising Young Woman\"!!!|website=[[Twitter.com]]|first=Emerald|last=Fennell|date=March 26, 2019|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn February 2019, [[Focus Features]] acquired distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/carey-mulligan-focus-filmnation-luckychap-sets-promising-young-woman-1202556617/|title=Focus Boards Carey Mulligan Thriller 'Promising Young Woman'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Mike|last=Fleming Jr|date=February 13, 2019|accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> It had its world premiere at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] on January 25, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sundance-2020-unveils-female-powered-lineup-taylor-swift-gloria-steinem-films-1259538?|title=Sundance Unveils Female-Powered Lineup Featuring Taylor Swift, Gloria Steinem, Abortion Road Trip Drama|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Tatiana|last=Siegel|date=December 4, 2019|accessdate=December 4, 2019}}</ref> It was scheduled to be released on April 17, 2020, however due to the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]] it was pulled from the schedule.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Focus-Features-to-Release-PROMISING-YOUNG-WOMAN-on-April-17-20191122|title=Focus Features to Release PROMISING YOUNG WOMAN on April 17|website=Broadway World|date=November 22, 2019|accessdate=December 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.focusfeatures.com/promising-young-woman|title=Promising Young Woman|website=Focus Features|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical reception ===\nOn [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 93% based on 46 reviews, and an [[average rating]] of 7.54/10. The site's critics consensus reads: \"A boldly provocative, timely thriller, ''Promising Young Woman'' is an auspicious feature debut for writer-director Emerald Fennell -- and a career highlight for Carey Mulligan.\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Promising Young Woman (2020)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/promising_young_woman|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 74 out of 100, based on 14 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Promising Young Woman Reviews|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/promising-young-woman|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDB title|9620292}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:2020s feminist films]]\n[[Category:2020s thriller films]]\n[[Category:2020s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:2020s vigilante films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American feminist films]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American vigilante films]]\n[[Category:2020 directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:FilmNation Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Margot Robbie]]\n[[Category:Focus Features films]]\n[[Category:LuckyChap Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Rape and revenge films]]\n", "name_user": "Draco9904", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Promising_Young_Woman"}
{"title_page": "Hugh Montgomery (physician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Hugh Montgomery\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = <!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')-->\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = Hugh Edward Montgomery\n| birth_date        ={{Birth date and age|df=y|1962|10|10}}<ref name=\"whoswho\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U254144 |title=Montgomery, Prof. Hugh Edward |work=Who's Who 2014, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2014; online edn, Oxford University Press }}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n| birth_place       = \n\n| other_names       = \n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = \n| fields            = Medicine\n| workplaces        = [[University College London]]\n| patrons           =\n| alma_mater        = [[Middlesex Hospital]] Medical School\n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = {{flatlist|\"Fitness gene\"\n*[[Royal Institution Christmas Lectures|Royal Institution Christmas lecturer]] (2007)}}\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = \n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           =  {{URL|https://twitter.com/hugh_montgomery}} \n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = \n| children          = \n}}'''Hugh Edward Montgomery''' (born 10 October 1962) is an English professor of medicine and the director of the UCL Institute for Human Health and Performance at [[University College London]]. He discovered that an [[allele]] of the gene with the DNA code for [[angiotensin-converting enzyme]] (ACE) influences physical fitness; this is the first discovery of a gene related to fitness.<ref name=\"ace\"/><ref>[http://www.ucl.ac.uk/slms/people/show.php?personid=11979 Prof Hugh Montgomery UCL] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090524145902/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/slms/people/show.php?personid=11979 |date=24 May 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\nMontgomery was educated at [[Plymouth College]] and qualified as a medical doctor in July 1987 from the Middlesex Hospital Medical School, University of London.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.gmc-uk.org/doctors/register/LRMP.asp|title=List of Registered Medical Practitioners (The online Register)|publisher=[[General Medical Council]] |accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> He leads a research group in cardiovascular genetics which has published over 100 publications including original research papers in journals such as ''Nature'', ''[[The Lancet]]'' and the ''New England Journal of Medicine''.<ref name=\"ace\">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/30374| pmid = 9607758| year = 1998| last1 = Montgomery | first1 = H. E.| authorlink1 = Hugh Montgomery (geneticist)| title = Human gene for physical performance| journal = Nature| volume = 393| issue = 6682| pages = 221\u20132| last2 = Marshall | first2 = R.| last3 = Hemingway | first3 = H.| last4 = Myerson | first4 = S.| last5 = Clarkson | first5 = P.| last6 = Dollery | first6 = C.| last7 = Hayward | first7 = M.| last8 = Holliman | first8 = D. E.| last9 = Jubb | first9 = M.| last10 = World | first10 = M.| last11 = Thomas | first11 = E. L.| last12 = Brynes | first12 = A. E.| last13 = Saeed | first13 = N.| last14 = Barnard | first14 = M.| last15 = Bell | first15 = J. D.| last16 = Prasad | first16 = K.| last17 = Rayson | first17 = M.| last18 = Talmud | first18 = P. J.| last19 = Humphries | first19 = S. E.}}</ref><ref name=\"scopus\">{{Scopus|id= 35482685300}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal\n | pmid = 19129527\n| year = 2009\n| last1 = Grocott\n| first1 = M. P.\n| title = Arterial blood gases and oxygen content in climbers on Mount Everest\n| journal = New England Journal of Medicine\n| volume = 360\n| issue = 2\n| pages = 140\u20139\n| last2 = Martin\n| first2 = D. S.\n| last3 = Levett\n| first3 = D. Z.\n| last4 = McMorrow\n| first4 = R\n| last5 = Windsor\n| first5 = J\n| last6 = Montgomery\n| first6 = H. E.\n| author7 = Caudwell Xtreme Everest Research Group\n| doi = 10.1056/NEJMoa0801581\n| url = http://eprints.brighton.ac.uk/14342/1/NEJM%20CXE%20ABG%202009.pdf\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(03)14286-9| pmid = 13678872| title = Efficacy of perindopril in reduction of cardiovascular events among patients with stable coronary artery disease: Randomised, double-blind, placebo-controlled, multicentre trial (the EUROPA study)| journal = The Lancet| volume = 362| issue = 9386| pages = 782\u2013788| year = 2003| last1 = Fox| first1 = K. M.| author2 = EURopean trial On reduction of cardiac events with Perindopril in stable coronary Artery disease Investigators}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(09)60935-1| pmid = 19447250| title = Managing the health effects of climate change| journal = The Lancet| volume = 373| issue = 9676| pages = 1693\u2013733| year = 2009| last1 = Costello | first1 = A. | last2 = Abbas | first2 = M. | last3 = Allen | first3 = A. | last4 = Ball | first4 = S. | last5 = Bell | first5 = S. | last6 = Bellamy | first6 = R. | last7 = Friel | first7 = S. | last8 = Groce | first8 = N. | last9 = Johnson | first9 = A. | last10 = Kett | first10 = M. | last11 = Lee | first11 = M. | last12 = Levy | first12 = C. | last13 = Maslin | first13 = M. | last14 = McCoy | first14 = D. | last15 = McGuire | first15 = B. | last16 = Montgomery | first16 = H. | last17 = Napier | first17 = D. | last18 = Pagel | first18 = C. | last19 = Patel | first19 = J. | last20 = De Oliveira | first20 = J. A. P. | last21 = Redclift | first21 = N. | last22 = Rees | first22 = H. | last23 = Rogger | first23 = D. | last24 = Scott | first24 = J. | last25 = Stephenson | first25 = J. | last26 = Twigg | first26 = J. | last27 = Wolff | first27 = J. | last28 = Patterson | first28 = C. }}</ref>\n\nHe is a Professor of [[Intensive-care medicine|Intensive Care Medicine]] at UCL and practises as a consultant in critical care at the [[Whittington Hospital]] in north London.{{cn|date=September 2018}}\n\n==Other interests==\nMontgomery has been awarded the title of London Leader by the London Sustainable Development Commission for his work in climate change and health under the auspices of Project Genie; he was also a founding member of the UK Climate and Health Council and one of the co-authors of the UCL-Lancet Commission in 2009.\nMontgomery has complemented his interest in fitness with achievements which include the 100&nbsp;km [[ultramarathon|ultra marathons]], holding the world record for underwater piano playing as well as visiting [[Everest]] with the Xtreme Everest research group to undertake research.<ref name=\"everest\">{{Cite journal\n | pmid = 20586597\n| year = 2010\n| last1 = Grocott\n| first1 = M. P.\n| title = Caudwell xtreme Everest expedition\n| journal = High Altitude Medicine & Biology\n| volume = 11\n| issue = 2\n| pages = 133\u20137\n| last2 = Martin\n| first2 = D. S.\n| last3 = Wilson\n| first3 = M. H.\n| last4 = Mitchell\n| first4 = K\n| last5 = Dhillon\n| first5 = S\n| last6 = Mythen\n| first6 = M. G.\n| last7 = Montgomery\n| first7 = H. E.\n| last8 = Levett\n| first8 = D. Z.\n| author9 = Caudwell Xtreme Everest Research Group\n\n| doi = 10.1089/ham.2009.1093\n| doi-access = free\n}}</ref>\n\nHe is the co-Editor-in-Chief of the Open Access journal ''Extreme Physiology & Medicine'' published by [[BioMed Central]].<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1186/2046-7648-1-1| pmid = 23849731| pmc = 3707096| title = Extreme Physiology & Medicine: A new journal focussed on integrative human physiology under stress| journal = Extreme Physiology & Medicine| volume = 1| issue = 1| pages = 1| year = 2012| last1 = Grocott | first1 = M. P. | last2 = Montgomery | first2 = H. E. }}</ref>\n\nMontgomery is the author of the children's book ''[[The Voyage of the Arctic Tern]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gordon|first1=Bryony|title=I'm Always Adding Strings to mMy Bow|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/4493031/Im-always-adding-strings-to-my-bow.html|accessdate=4 February 2017|agency=The Telegraph (U.K.)|date=11 June 2002}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n*2007 Presented the televised annual [[Royal Institution Christmas Lectures]] on the subject ''Back from the brink: the science of survival''.<ref>[http://richannel.org/christmas-lectures/2007/hugh-montgomery Royal Institution Christmas Lectures 2007: ''Back from the brink: the science of survival'']</ref><ref>[http://www.richannel.org/ri-unconference-hugh-montgomery--science-and-the-environment, Hugh Montgomery address on Science & Environment], [[Royal Institution]] Unconference, September 2011</ref>\n*2010 Chosen to present the [[Ellison-Cliffe Lecture]] at the [[Royal Society of Medicine]].{{cn|date=September 2018}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Montgomery, Hugh}}\n[[Category:Academics of University College London]]\n[[Category:21st-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:People from Plymouth]]\n[[Category:People educated at Plymouth College]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Hugh Montgomery\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = <!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')-->\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = Hugh Edward Montgomery\n| birth_date        ={{Birth date and age|df=y|1962|10|10}}<ref name=\"whoswho\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U254144 |title=