{"title_page": "Bernie Clifton", "text_new": "{{short description|British comedian and entertainer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Bernie Clifton\n| occupation = Entertainer\n| birth_name = Bernard M Quinn\n| birth_date = 30 April 1936\n| birth_place = [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]], [[Lancashire]], England\n}}\n\n'''Bernie Clifton''' (born '''Bernard M Quinn''')<ref name=BBCNewsJan2016>{{cite news |title=Bernie Clifton auditions on The Voice |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35271062 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=9 January 2016}}</ref> is a British comedian and entertainer, known best for his work with his orange [[ostrich]] puppet costume Oswald the Ostrich.<ref name=JamiesonSep2017/>\n\n==Career==\nClifton's first performing job was as a singer with a dance band, however he was fired after a month.<ref name=JamiesonSep2017/> His first television performance was on the light entertainment show ''[[The Good Old Days (British TV series)|The Good Old Days]]'', where he was inspired by [[Les Dawson]].<ref name=JamiesonSep2017/>\n\nHe performed in the 1979 ''[[Royal Variety Performance]]''.<ref name=WardJan2016>{{cite news |last1=Ward |first1=Rachel |title=Bernie Clifton moves Ricky Wilson to tears after surprise performance on The Voice |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/the-voice/12091640/Bernie-Clifton-surprise-appearance-The-Voice-ricky-wilson.html |work=The Telegraph |date=10 January 2016 |language=en}}</ref> Since then he has performed in it several times, including 2016.<ref name=LawrenceDec2016>{{cite news |last1=Lawrence |first1=Ben |title=Is the Royal Variety Performance still fit for a king (or queen)? |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2016/12/13/royal-variety-performance-still-fit-king-queen/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=13 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe was a regular appearance on ''[[Crackerjack! (TV series)|Crackerjack!]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Anita |title=Crackerjack makes a comeback: BBC revives children's show for a new generation |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/02/11/crackerjack-makes-comeback-bbc-revives-retro-kids-show-new-generation/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=11 February 2019}}</ref> During the 1980s, he appeared on ''[[The Keith Harris Show]]'',<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Anita |title=Keith Harris, Orville ventriloquist, dies at 67 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/11567842/Keith-Harris-Orville-ventriloquist-dies-at-67.html |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=28 April 2015}}</ref> and in 1982, Clifton ran the [[London Marathon]] with Oswald the Ostrich.<ref name=BBCNewsJan2016/>\n\nIn 2002, Clifton featured on the BBC2 documentary series ''The Entertainers'', which followed 1970s and 80s entertainers who had dropped out of the limelight.<ref name=SmithSep2002>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Rupert |title=A generation of TV veterans are back |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/sep/16/broadcasting.tvandradio |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=16 September 2002}}</ref> In 2005, Clifton and Oswald appeared in the music video for [[Peter Kay]] and [[Tony Christie]]'s [[Comic Relief]] version of \"[[(Is This the Way to) Amarillo]]\".<ref name=WardJan2016/>\n\nIn 2005 Clifton appeared as himself in an episode of the [[David Renwick]] sitcom [[Love Soup]] after previously being mentioned by Renwick in an early episode of [[One Foot in the Grave]].<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0636925/reference</ref>\n\nHe made his [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] debut in 2006 at the Udderbelly venue. Writing in ''[[The Guardian]]'', Brian Logan gave it 3 out of 5 stars and called it an \"exercise in retro comedy\", but \"also unrepentantly funny\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Logan |first1=Brian |title=Bernie Clifton, Udderbelly, Edinburgh |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2006/aug/17/comedy.edinburgh20061 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=17 August 2006}}</ref>\n\nClifton was a contestant on [[The Voice UK (series 5)|Series 5]] of ''[[The Voice UK]]'', applying under his birth name. He performed \"[[The Impossible Dream (The Quest)]]\" from ''[[Man of La Mancha]]'', and did not advance past the blind auditions.<ref name=BBCNewsJan2016/> Following his appearance on the show he released an album of covers called ''The Impossible Dream'', which included \"[[The Lady in Red (Chris de Burgh song)|The Lady in Red]]\" and \"[[Wind Beneath My Wings]]\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Bernie Clifton in death metal mix-up |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-36129559 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=25 April 2016}}</ref> After a death metal band's song titles were printed on his album cover by mistake, Clifton presented an award at the [[Kerrang! Awards|''Kerrang!'' Awards]] in June 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bernie Clifton to go to Kerrang! Awards |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-36378371 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=9 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, he starred in [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]]'s ''Last Laugh in Vegas'', a documentary following eight \"showbiz legends\" as they prepare a show in [[Las Vegas]].<ref name=LastLaugh>{{cite web |title=Last Laugh In Vegas - ITV Factual |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/last_laugh_in_vegas/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |website=British Comedy Guide}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Clifton appeared as a guest on the first episode of the new series of ''Crackerjack!'' on [[CBBC]].<ref name=CBBC2020>{{cite web |title=CBBC - Crackerjack!, Series 1, One |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m000ddhl |accessdate=4 March 2020 |website=BBC}}</ref> In February, he played himself in the first episode of ''Meet The Richardsons'' on [[Dave (TV channel)|Dave]].<ref name=RichardsonsEp1>{{cite news |last1=Guide |first1=British Comedy |title=Meet The Richardsons Series 1, Episode 1 |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/meet_the_richardsons/episodes/1/1/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=British Comedy Guide}}</ref> Within the episode, he is a family friend of [[Jon Richardson]] and teaches him how to operate a monkey puppet similar to his ostrich.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Young |first1=Lottie |title=Meet The Richardsons offers a peek into the life of a comedy couple |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/tvfilm/meet-the-richardsons-review-a4373506.html |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=Evening Standard |date=27 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nClifton has starred in several [[pantomimes]], playing the father of [[Cinderella]] at the [[Hull New Theatre]] in 2018 and at [[Northampton]]'s [[Royal & Derngate]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wiser |first1=Danny |title=Pantomime starring Anita Dobson criticised as 'sexist and lewd' as audience walk out during show |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/12/23/pantomime-starring-anita-dobson-criticised-sexist-lewd-audience/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=23 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mooney |first1=Lauren |title=Cinderella review at Royal and Derngate, Northampton |url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/2019/cinderella-anita-dobson-bernie-clifton-review-at-royal-and-derngate-northampton/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Stage |date=11 December 2019}}</ref> He has also presented various shows on [[BBC Radio Sheffield]],<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Radio Sheffield - Live-ish, 23/03/2019 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p072qk3z |website=BBC |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Radio Sheffield - BBC Radio Sheffield Special, The Golden Days of Working Men's Clubs |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02r9fzy |website=BBC |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> and [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hepworth |first1=David |title=Next week's radio: from Richard Tauber Revived to Studio 360 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2013/oct/26/david-hepworth-radio-review |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=26 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Daoust |first1=Phil |title=Radio pick of the day: The Material World {{!}} Under the Skin {{!}} The Pallisers |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/dec/28/tvandradio.radio |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=28 December 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nClifton was born on 30 April 1936 in [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]], Lancashire where he also grew up.<ref name=JamiesonSep2017>{{cite news |last1=Jamieson |first1=Georgy |title=Bernie Clifton interview |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/people/bernie_clifton/features/2017_interview/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=British Comedy Guide |date=16 September 2017}}</ref><ref>https://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/districts.pl?r=172731578:7272&d=bmd_1586250123</ref><ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1101543/bio?ref_=nm_ql_1</ref>\n\nIn 1961 Clifton married Marjorie Hancock, they went on to have four children together. Clifton was widowed in 2000.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1101543/bio?ref_=nm_ql_1</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n! {{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|1979\n|''Royal Variety Performance''\n|Himself\n|\n|<ref name=WardJan2016/>\n|-\n|2002\n|''The Entertainers''\n|Himself\n|\n|<ref name=SmithSep2002/>\n|-\n|2005\n|''Love Soup''\n|Himself\n|series 1 episode 4\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[The Voice UK]]''\n|Himself\n|[[The Voice UK (series 5)|series 5]], episode 1\n|<ref name=BBCNewsJan2016/><ref name=WardJan2016/>\n|-\n|2016\n|''Royal Variety Performance''\n|Himself\n|\n|<ref name=LawrenceDec2016/>\n|-\n|2018\n|''Last Laugh in Vegas''\n|Himself\n|5 episodes\n|<ref name=LastLaugh/>\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Crackerjack! (TV series)|Crackerjack!]]''\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|<ref name=CBBC2020/>\n|-\n|2020\n|''Meet The Richardsons''\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|<ref name=RichardsonsEp1/>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=1101543|name=Bernie Clifton}}\n*[http://www.bernieclifton.co.uk/ Website]\n\n{{The Voice UK}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clifton, Bernie}}\n[[Category:British comedians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from St Helens, Merseyside]]\n\n{{UK-comedian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British comedian and entertainer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Bernie Clifton\n| occupation = Entertainer\n| birth_name = Bernard Quinn\n| birth_date =  {{Birth year and age|1936|04}}\n| birth_place = [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]], [[Lancashire]], England\n}}\n\n'''Bernie Clifton''' (born '''Bernard Quinn''')<ref name=BBCNewsJan2016>{{cite news |title=Bernie Clifton auditions on The Voice |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35271062 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=9 January 2016}}</ref> is a British comedian and entertainer, known best for his work with his orange [[ostrich]] puppet costume Oswald the Ostrich.<ref name=JamiesonSep2017/>\n\n==Early life==\nClifton grew up in [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]], Lancashire.<ref name=JamiesonSep2017>{{cite news |last1=Jamieson |first1=Georgy |title=Bernie Clifton interview |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/people/bernie_clifton/features/2017_interview/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=British Comedy Guide |date=16 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nClifton's first performing job was as a singer with a dance band, however he was fired after a month.<ref name=JamiesonSep2017/> His first television performance was on the light entertainment show ''[[The Good Old Days (British TV series)|The Good Old Days]]'', where he was inspired by [[Les Dawson]].<ref name=JamiesonSep2017/>\n\nHe performed in the 1979 ''[[Royal Variety Performance]]''.<ref name=WardJan2016>{{cite news |last1=Ward |first1=Rachel |title=Bernie Clifton moves Ricky Wilson to tears after surprise performance on The Voice |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/the-voice/12091640/Bernie-Clifton-surprise-appearance-The-Voice-ricky-wilson.html |work=The Telegraph |date=10 January 2016 |language=en}}</ref> Since then he has performed in it several times, including 2016.<ref name=LawrenceDec2016>{{cite news |last1=Lawrence |first1=Ben |title=Is the Royal Variety Performance still fit for a king (or queen)? |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2016/12/13/royal-variety-performance-still-fit-king-queen/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=13 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe was a regular appearance on ''[[Crackerjack! (TV series)|Crackerjack!]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Anita |title=Crackerjack makes a comeback: BBC revives children's show for a new generation |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/02/11/crackerjack-makes-comeback-bbc-revives-retro-kids-show-new-generation/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=11 February 2019}}</ref> During the 1980s, he appeared on ''[[The Keith Harris Show]]'',<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Anita |title=Keith Harris, Orville ventriloquist, dies at 67 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/11567842/Keith-Harris-Orville-ventriloquist-dies-at-67.html |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=28 April 2015}}</ref> and in 1982, Clifton ran the [[London Marathon]] with Oswald the Ostrich.<ref name=BBCNewsJan2016/>\n\nIn 2002, Clifton featured on the BBC2 documentary series ''The Entertainers'', which followed 1970s and 80s entertainers who had dropped out of the limelight.<ref name=SmithSep2002>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Rupert |title=A generation of TV veterans are back |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/sep/16/broadcasting.tvandradio |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=16 September 2002}}</ref> In 2005, Clifton and Oswald appeared in the music video for [[Peter Kay]] and [[Tony Christie]]'s [[Comic Relief]] version of \"[[(Is This the Way to) Amarillo]]\".<ref name=WardJan2016/> \n\nHe made his [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] debut in 2006 at the Udderbelly venue. Writing in ''[[The Guardian]]'', Brian Logan gave it 3 out of 5 stars and called it an \"exercise in retro comedy\", but \"also unrepentantly funny\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Logan |first1=Brian |title=Bernie Clifton, Udderbelly, Edinburgh |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2006/aug/17/comedy.edinburgh20061 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=17 August 2006}}</ref>\n\nClifton was a contestant on [[The Voice UK (series 5)|Series 5]] of ''[[The Voice UK]]'', applying under his birth name. He performed \"[[The Impossible Dream (The Quest)]]\" from ''[[Man of La Mancha]]'', and did not advance past the blind auditions.<ref name=BBCNewsJan2016/> Following his appearance on the show he released an album of covers called ''The Impossible Dream'', which included \"[[The Lady in Red (Chris de Burgh song)|The Lady in Red]]\" and \"[[Wind Beneath My Wings]]\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Bernie Clifton in death metal mix-up |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-36129559 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=25 April 2016}}</ref> After a death metal band's song titles were printed on his album cover by mistake, Clifton presented an award at the [[Kerrang! Awards|''Kerrang!'' Awards]] in June 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bernie Clifton to go to Kerrang! Awards |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-36378371 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=9 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, he starred in [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]]'s ''Last Laugh in Vegas'', a documentary following eight \"showbiz legends\" as they prepare a show in [[Las Vegas]].<ref name=LastLaugh>{{cite web |title=Last Laugh In Vegas - ITV Factual |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/last_laugh_in_vegas/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |website=British Comedy Guide}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Clifton appeared as a guest on the first episode of the new series of ''Crackerjack!'' on [[CBBC]].<ref name=CBBC2020>{{cite web |title=CBBC - Crackerjack!, Series 1, One |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m000ddhl |accessdate=4 March 2020 |website=BBC}}</ref> In February, he played himself in the first episode of ''Meet The Richardsons'' on [[Dave (TV channel)|Dave]].<ref name=RichardsonsEp1>{{cite news |last1=Guide |first1=British Comedy |title=Meet The Richardsons Series 1, Episode 1 |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/meet_the_richardsons/episodes/1/1/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=British Comedy Guide}}</ref> Within the episode, he is a family friend of [[Jon Richardson]] and teaches him how to operate a monkey puppet similar to his ostrich.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Young |first1=Lottie |title=Meet The Richardsons offers a peek into the life of a comedy couple |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/tvfilm/meet-the-richardsons-review-a4373506.html |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=Evening Standard |date=27 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nClifton has starred in several [[pantomimes]], playing the father of [[Cinderella]] at the [[Hull New Theatre]] in 2018 and at [[Northampton]]'s [[Royal & Derngate]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wiser |first1=Danny |title=Pantomime starring Anita Dobson criticised as 'sexist and lewd' as audience walk out during show |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/12/23/pantomime-starring-anita-dobson-criticised-sexist-lewd-audience/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=23 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mooney |first1=Lauren |title=Cinderella review at Royal and Derngate, Northampton |url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/2019/cinderella-anita-dobson-bernie-clifton-review-at-royal-and-derngate-northampton/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Stage |date=11 December 2019}}</ref> He has also presented various shows on [[BBC Radio Sheffield]],<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Radio Sheffield - Live-ish, 23/03/2019 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p072qk3z |website=BBC |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Radio Sheffield - BBC Radio Sheffield Special, The Golden Days of Working Men's Clubs |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02r9fzy |website=BBC |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> and [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hepworth |first1=David |title=Next week's radio: from Richard Tauber Revived to Studio 360 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2013/oct/26/david-hepworth-radio-review |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=26 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Daoust |first1=Phil |title=Radio pick of the day: The Material World {{!}} Under the Skin {{!}} The Pallisers |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/dec/28/tvandradio.radio |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=28 December 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n! {{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|1979\n|''Royal Variety Performance''\n|Himself\n|\n|<ref name=WardJan2016/>\n|-\n|2002\n|''The Entertainers''\n|Himself\n|\n|<ref name=SmithSep2002/>\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[The Voice UK]]''\n|Himself\n|[[The Voice UK (series 5)|Series 5]], episode 1\n|<ref name=BBCNewsJan2016/><ref name=WardJan2016/>\n|-\n|2016\n|''Royal Variety Performance''\n|Himself\n|\n|<ref name=LawrenceDec2016/>\n|-\n|2018\n|''Last Laugh in Vegas''\n|Himself\n|5 episodes\n|<ref name=LastLaugh/>\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Crackerjack! (TV series)|Crackerjack!]]''\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|<ref name=CBBC2020/>\n|-\n|2020\n|''Meet The Richardsons''\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|<ref name=RichardsonsEp1/>\n|}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=1101543|name=Bernie Clifton}}\n* [http://www.bernieclifton.co.uk/ Website]\n\n{{The Voice UK}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clifton, Bernie}}\n[[Category:British comedians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from St Helens, Merseyside]]\n\n{{UK-comedian-stub}}\n", "name_user": "BabsEverAfter", "label": "safe", "comment": "Revert Troll", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernie_Clifton"}
{"title_page": "December 2013 Spuyten Duyvil derailment", "text_new": "{{short description|Passenger commuter train accident that killed four}}\n{{about|the passenger train that derailed at Spuyten Duyvil in December 2013|the freight train that derailed nearby in July of the same year|July 2013 Spuyten Duyvil derailment}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Use American English|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox public transit accident\n| name                = Spuyten Duyvil derailment (December 2013)\n<!-- Image          -->\n| image               = NTSBSpuytenDuyvilDerailment2013.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| image_alt           = An aerial view of a wooded area between two watery areas in late autumn, with two railroad tracks forking to the top near the left and one following the water's edge. Several silvery train cars and a locomotive are lying on their sides off the tracks to the top; there are many parked yellow and white trucks and other vehicles between the two tracks.\n| caption             = Aerial view of the derailment\n<!-- Maps           -->\n| image_map           = \n| image_map_alt       = \n| image_map_caption   = \n| pushpin_map         = \n| alternative_map     = \n| pushpin_map_alt     = \n| pushpin_map_caption = \n| mapframe            = \n| qid                 = \n| mapframe_zoom       = \n| coordinates         = {{Coord|40.879597|N|73.922829|W|format=dms|type:event_region:US-NY_scale:50000|display=inline,title}}\n<!-- Details        -->\n| date                = December 1, 2013\n| time                = 7:19 a.m. [[Eastern Standard Time (North America)|EST]] (12:19 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]])\n| location            = Near [[Spuyten Duyvil (Metro-North station)|Spuyten Duyvil station]]\n| location_dir        = \n| location_city       = The Bronx, [[New York City|NY]]\n| location_dist_km    = \n| location_dist_mi    = \n| country             = United States\n| line                = [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]]\n| operator            = [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|MTA]], [[Metro-North Railroad]]\n| owner               = \n| service             = \n| type                = [[Derailment]]\n| cause               = Driver error, overspeeding\n<!-- Statistics     --> \n| bus                 = \n| trains              = 1\n| vehicles            = \n| passengers          = 115\n| crew                = \n| pedestrians         = \n| deaths              = 4\n| injuries            = At least 61\n| damage              = $9 million<ref name=\"NTSB brief\">{{cite web|title=Railroad Accident Brief: Metro-North Derailment|url=http://www.ntsb.gov/doclib/reports/2014/RAB1412.pdf|publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|date=October 24, 2014|accessdate=October 30, 2014}}</ref>\n| property            = \n<!-- Route map      -->\n| route_map           = \n| route_map_state     = \n| route_map_name      = \n<!-- Footnotes      --> \n| footnotes           = \n}}\nOn the morning of December 1, 2013, a [[Metro-North Railroad]] [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]] passenger train [[derailment|derailed]] near the [[Spuyten Duyvil (Metro-North station)|Spuyten Duyvil station]] in the [[New York City]] borough of [[the Bronx]]. Four of about 115 passengers were killed and another 61 injured; the accident caused $9 million worth of damage.<ref name=\"NTSB brief\" /> It was the deadliest [[train wreck|train accident]] within New York City since a [[1991 Union Square derailment|1991 subway derailment]] in lower [[Manhattan]],<ref name=\"wp\">{{cite news|first=Emily|last=Thibodeaux|title=Train derailment in New York City leaves four dead, dozens injured; NTSB investigating|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/nyc-train-derailment-leaves-4-dead-dozens-injured/2013/12/01/d180a0fe-5aa1-11e3-bf7e-f567ee61ae21_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=December 1, 2013|accessdate=December 6, 2013}}</ref> and the first accident in Metro-North's history to result in passenger fatalities.<ref name=\"NYT investigation story\">{{cite news|last1=Barron|first1=James|last2=Goodman|first2=J. David|title=Focus Turns to Investigation in Fatal Bronx Train Crash|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/02/nyregion/metro-north-derailment.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref> The additional $60 million in legal claims paid out {{as of|2020|lc=yes}} have also made it the costliest accident in Metro-North's history.<ref name=\"2018 lawsuit followup story\">{{cite news|last=Zambito|first=Thomas C.|title=Spuyten Duyvil derailment: Five years later - lawsuits, payouts and blame for Metro-North|url=https://www.lohud.com/story/news/investigations/2018/11/28/lawsuits-payouts-wake-2013-spuyten-duyvil-derailment/2060225002/|newspaper=[[The Journal News]]|date=November 28, 2018|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly investigations found that the train had gone into the curve where it derailed at almost three times the posted speed limit. The engineer, William Rockefeller, later admitted that before reaching the curve he had gone into a \"daze\", a sort of [[highway hypnosis]].\n\nThe leader of the [[National Transportation Safety Board]] (NTSB) team investigating said it was likely that the accident would have been prevented had [[positive train control]] (PTC) been installed per a prior federal mandate requiring its installation by 2015. Due to a number of other recent accidents involving Metro-North trains and tracks, the [[Federal Railroad Administration]] (FRA) demanded improved safety measures, which Metro-North began implementing within a week of the accident.\n\nIn late 2014, almost a year after the accident, the NTSB released its final report on the accident. After reiterating its earlier conclusion that PTC would have prevented the accident entirely, it found the most direct cause was Rockefeller's inattention as the train entered the curve. There were other contributing factors. A medical examination following the accident diagnosed [[sleep apnea]], which had hampered his ability to fully adjust his sleep patterns to the morning shift which he had begun working two weeks earlier. The report faulted both Metro-North for not screening its employees in sensitive positions for [[sleep disorder]]s, and the FRA for not requiring railroads to do such screening.<ref name=\"NTSB brief\" />\n\n=={{anchor|Train}}Background==\n\nThe train involved in the accident was the second southbound [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]] train of the day, leaving [[Poughkeepsie (Metro-North station)|Poughkeepsie]], the line's northern terminus, at its scheduled departure time of 5:54&nbsp;a.m. [[Eastern Standard Time (North America)|EST]].<ref name=\"current Metro-North schedule\">[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]], {{cite web|url= http://web.mta.info/mnr/html/planning/schedules/pdf/NOV172013HUD-SS.pdf |title=Hudson Line weekend schedule|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|date= November 17, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216041718/http://www.mta.info/mnr/html/planning/schedules/pdf/NOV172013HUD-SS.pdf|archivedate=December 16, 2013|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> It was powered by a [[GE Genesis|GE P32AC-DM]] [[dual-mode locomotive|locomotive]],<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript\">{{cite web|title=Transcript of Interview 8808 Engineer|url=http://dms.ntsb.gov/public%2F55500-55999%2F55841%2F551511.pdf|publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|page=48|date=December 3, 2013|accessdate=October 31, 2014}}</ref> capable of running on either diesel fuel or electricity from a [[third rail]]. Since Metro-North uses [[Push\u2013pull train#Locomotive at one end|push-pull trains]], it was situated at the northern, or rear, end of the train to minimize noise on the underground platforms at [[Grand Central Terminal]] in Manhattan, its final destination,<ref name=\"NYT alerter story\">{{cite news|last1=Flegenheimer|first1=Matt|last2=Fessenden|first2=Ford|last3=Fountain|first3=Henry|title=Train Had a Warning System, Just Not in the Operator's Cab|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/05/nyregion/as-metro-north-resumes-service-riders-get-back-to-routine.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 5, 2013|accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> where it was scheduled to arrive at 7:43.<ref name=\"current Metro-North schedule\" />  It carried about 115 passengers.<ref name=\"NTSB brief\" />\n[[File:Metro-North Shoreliner IV 6222.jpg|thumb|left|The lead train car involved in the derailment, pictured in 2009 leading a [[Harlem Line]] train into [[North White Plains (Metro-North station)|North White Plains]]|alt=A train headed by a light gray car with a red stripe on the side on a track between two others in a walled area moving from right to left across the image. On its front is the number 6222.]]\nEngineer William Rockefeller, a 15-year Metro-North veteran who had started as a clerk in the [[stationmaster]]'s office at Grand Central and then spent 10 years as an engineer, was operating the train from the [[cab car]], at the front of a [[wikt:consist#Noun|consist]] of seven [[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier]]-made [[Shoreliner]] passenger coaches,<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript\" /> in a mix of Metro-North and [[Connecticut Department of Transportation]] livery,{{efn|The two agencies share equipment for operation on the non-electrified [[Danbury Branch|Danbury]] and [[Waterbury Branch|Waterbury]] branches of the [[New Haven Line]].}} two of which were closed off and used only for [[Dead mileage#Deadheading|deadheading]] by employees.<ref name=\"Hermann interview transcript\">{{cite web|title=Transcript of Interview Conductor|url=http://dms.ntsb.gov/public%2F55500-55999%2F55841%2F551523.pdf|publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|page=36|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=November 1, 2014}}</ref> He had recently begun working the morning shift after working afternoons, a change he later told investigators he had made reluctantly,<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript 23\">''8808 Engineer'', 23.</ref> requiring that he leave his home in [[Germantown (town), New York|Germantown]], approximately {{convert|27|mi}} north of Poughkeepsie, at 3:30&nbsp;a.m. for work. To make sure he had adequate rest before his shift, he had gone to bed at 8:30&nbsp;p.m. the night before following a nine-hour shift the preceding day.<ref name=\"Rockland Times story\" /> He had arrived at work on time after a 43-minute drive, after which he bought a cup of coffee and a [[hard roll]], filled out paperwork and attended a standard safety briefing, followed by tests of the train's safety equipment.<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript 6\">''8808 Engineer'', 5-6</ref> Another veteran employee, Michael Hermann, who in his limited time working with Rockefeller had praised the engineer's \"very smooth\" train handling to other Metro-North employees,<ref name=\"Hermann interview transcript 50\">''Conductor'', 50.</ref> was the [[Conductor (transportation)#Conductors in North America|conductor]]; his one assistant leaving Poughkeepsie was Maria Herbert, with whom he regularly worked.<ref name=\"Hermann interview transcript 39-40\">''Conductor'', 39-40.</ref>\n\nOnce underway in predawn darkness that gradually lightened to [[civil twilight]],<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript 19\">''8808 Engineer'', 19</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=December 2013 \u2014 Sun in Poughkeepsie|url=https://www.timeanddate.com/sun/usa/poughkeepsie?month=12&year=2013|publisher=timeanddate.com|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> the train proceeded south along the two-track main line, also used by [[Amtrak]] for its [[Empire Service (train)|Empire Service]] trains. From Poughkeepsie it continued through the mid- and lower [[Hudson Valley]], often right next to  [[Hudson River|the river]]. Under [[electromotor]] diesel power, it made all six of its scheduled stops in the upper, non-electrified portion of the Hudson Line in [[Dutchess County, New York|Dutchess]], [[Putnam County, New York|Putnam]] and [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester]] counties without incident. After [[Croton-Harmon (Metro-North station)|Croton-Harmon]], the northern end of the line's [[Railway electrification system|electrification]], where it picked up another assistant conductor, Chris Kelly, it was held up briefly.<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript 7\">''8808 Engineer'', 7</ref> The next stop was [[Ossining (Metro-North station)|Ossining]], where it became an [[Express train|express]], continuing under diesel power.{{efn|Despite the presence of electrification, Metro-North's dual-mode trains use it only when they enter the [[Park Avenue Tunnel (railroad)|Park Avenue Tunnel]], since New York City bans the use of diesel locomotives in tunnels. Similar bans apply to the [[Long Island Rail Road]], where diesel trains must also be dual-mode.}} Between Ossining and the last stop, [[Tarrytown (Metro-North station)|Tarrytown]],<ref name=\"current Metro-North schedule\" /> just after dawn,<ref>{{cite web|title=December 2013 \u2014 Sun in Yonkers|url=https://www.timeanddate.com/sun/usa/yonkers?month=12&year=2013|publisher=timeanddate.com|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> Hermann and Herbert swept toward the center of the train, where they met briefly. After Tarrytown, with the train running only a minute behind schedule,<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript 34\">''8808 Engineer'', 34.</ref> they began returning to opposite ends of the train, taking seat checks from any passengers who might have boarded there. They were positioning themselves for where Metro-North's rules required them to be, so Herbert could join Rockefeller in the cab and call out signals after the last stop, [[Harlem\u2013125th Street (Metro-North station)|Harlem\u2013125th Street]]. Hermann, in the rear deadhead car with what he estimated to be six other employees, including Kelly, whom he had instructed to do so as the train's light passenger load did not require a third conductor, began doing his paperwork for the trip and preparing for his next.<ref name=\"Hermann interview transcript 39-40\" />\n\nThe train continued south over the next {{convert|14|mi}}<ref name=\"NTSB brief\" /> on a straight set of four tracks next to the river, all with third rails, past the four stations along the line in the city of [[Yonkers, New York|Yonkers]], a permanent speed restriction of {{convert|50|mph}} through downtown was augmented by a temporary {{cvt|60|mph|adj=on}} limit around [[Ludlow (Metro-North station)|Ludlow]] due to construction.<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript 8\">''8808 Engineer'', 8</ref> South of that station the train entered [[the Bronx]]. About {{convert|1.5|mi}} south of the [[Riverdale (Metro-North station)|Riverdale]] station, Rockefeller should have begun to slow the train down in anticipation of the curve<ref name=\"Daily News Harrod story\">{{cite news|last=Donohue|first=Pete|title='It looks bad for the engineer' of derailed Metro-North train: Safety pro|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/bad-engineer-derailed-train-pro-article-1.1535632|newspaper=[[New York Daily News]]|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 6, 2013}}</ref> immediately before [[Spuyten Duyvil (Metro-North station)|Spuyten Duyvil station]], below the [[Henry Hudson Bridge]] where the [[Harlem River Ship Canal]] flows into the Hudson across from the northern tip of Manhattan Island. Instead, he later said:\n{{quote|I [don]'t know how to explain it ... it was sort of like I was dazed, you know, looking straight ahead, almost like mesmerized. And I don't know if anybody's ever experienced like [[highway hypnosis|driving a long period of time in a car and staring at the taillights in front of them, and you get almost like that hypnotic feeling staring straight ahead]] ...  I was just staring straight ahead ... [it was] that hypnotized feeling, dazed, that's what I was [feeling].<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript 8\" />}}\n\nIt was interrupted when, he felt, \"something wasn't right with [the train].\"<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript 8\" /> Linda Smith, of [[Newburgh (city), New York|Newburgh]], who had boarded the train at [[Beacon (Metro-North station)|Beacon]] with her sister Donna to see a choral performance at [[Lincoln Center]], recalled that although she, too, was not fully awake, something seemed wrong. \"It was bumpy and just seemed really at that point I was aware of going very fast.\"<ref name=\"THR survivor account\">{{cite news|last=Nani|first=James|title=Derailment: Sister lives with memory of tragic ride and loss of best friend Donna Smith|url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20131204/NEWS/312040324/-1/NEWS98|newspaper=[[Times Herald-Record]]|location=[[Middletown, Orange County, New York|Middletown, NY]]|date=December 4, 2013|accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> In the cab, Rockefeller initiated an emergency application of the brakes in an attempt to slow the train down, but it was already taking the curve.<ref name=\"Daily News Harrod story\" />\n\n==Accident==\n[[File:Spuyten Duyvil derailment site map.svg|right|thumb|Map of derailment site, with cars shown in red|alt=A map showing the accident site, with the cars depicted as red lines]]\nAt 7:19&nbsp;a.m. the train derailed {{convert|100|yd|m}} north of the Spuyten Duyvil station, {{convert|11.4|mi}} north of Grand Central,<ref name=\"NTSB brief\" /> just after it had passed the junction with the [[West Side Line]]'s crossing over the [[Spuyten Duyvil Bridge]], where Amtrak's trains split off to go to [[Penn Station (New York)|Penn Station]]. In her passenger car, Linda Smith recalled the train turning sideways as the bumps she had felt gave way to bounces and seat cushions flew through the air. \"It was like a movie going on around me.\"<ref name=\"THR survivor account\" /> Debris entered the cars through the broken windows.<ref name=\"Rockland Times story\">{{cite news|last=Demarest|first=Bill|title=Focus in Probe of Deadly Metro-North Derailment Turns to Engineer|url=http://www.rocklandtimes.com/2013/12/04/focus-in-probe-of-deadly-metro-north-derailment-turns-to-engineer/|newspaper=Rockland County Times|date=December 4, 2013|accessdate=December 6, 2013}}</ref> Joel Zaritsky, a dentist from [[LaGrangeville, New York|LaGrangeville]] headed to a convention, said it was like \"severe turbulence on an airplane.\"<ref name=\"PoJo survivor account\">{{cite news|last=Schutzman|first=Nina|title='I Realized I was Alive...' My story of the chaos when my Metro-North train flipped and crashed|url=http://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/article/20131208/NEWS01/312080054/metro-north-train-derailment|newspaper=[[Poughkeepsie Journal]]|date=December 8, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the rear deadhead car, Hermann first heard \"a little bit of like a metallic rattling,\" which was by itself not an unusual sound, but it just sounded a little bit odd.\" He recalled to investigators a day later that \"the next thing I know my car had kicked and I was thrown from the fourth seat or across the coach up to the ceiling ... I dropped down. I went back up again and I slammed into the ceiling and then I slammed down into the floor.\"<ref name=\"Conductor interview 9-11\">''Conductor'', 9\u201311</ref> In the front, Herbert was sitting in the passenger seat behind the cab when \"I looked up just to do what I was doing and a split second [later] I'm tumbling on the floor ... I think I hit the ceiling several times. I didn't even have time to react or to think what I was doing.\"<ref name=\"Herbert interview transcript\">{{cite web|title=Transcript of Interview Assistant Conductor 1|url=http://dms.ntsb.gov/public%2F55500-55999%2F55841%2F551517.pdf|publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|page=7|date=December 3, 2013|accessdate=November 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWhen the train came to rest, Hermann, despite a [[head injury]] and some bruises, took charge and reported the derailment to the dispatcher. He then worked with Kelly to coordinate the passengers and the emergency responders.<ref name=\"Conductor interview 9-11\" /> In the front Rockefeller, who was mostly uninjured, freed Herbert, who was conscious but had also suffered a head injury, from the seat cushions that had piled up on her. Seeing that Hermann and Kelley had taken charge of the situation, he remained with her until he was taken to a hospital to be examined.<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview 10-11\">''8808 Engineer'', 10\u201311</ref>\n\nAll seven cars and the locomotive left the tracks. Those in the rear remained next to the tracks; in the front, the cab came to rest just short of the Harlem River. Rockefeller, largely unhurt, got out and began aiding passengers. Trapped under seat cushions, Smith, too, was uninjured but unable to move; her sister was thrown from the train and was one of the four killed in the accident.<ref name=\"THR survivor account\" /> Linda Smith was one of the 61<ref name=\"NTSB brief\" /> injured.<ref name=BBC25176496>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-25176496 |title=New York train crash: Metro-North derailment in Bronx |publisher=BBC News Online |accessdate=December 1, 2013 |date=December 1, 2013}}</ref><ref name=BH011213>{{cite web |url=http://bostonherald.com/news_opinion/national/northeast/2013/12/governor_4_dead_63_hurt_in_nyc_train_derailment |title=Governor: 4 dead, 63 hurt in NYC train derailment |publisher=The Boston Herald |accessdate=December 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Fatalities ===\n\nOf the four killed,{{efn|\nThe four people killed were: \n* Kisook Ahn, 35, of [[Queens]]<ref name=\"Daily news victims story\">{{cite news|last1=Sit|first1=Ryan|last2=Scarborough|first2=Joey|last3=Moore|first3=Tina|title=Metro-North crash victims include loving dad, friendly roommate, 'inseparable' sister|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/metro-north-crash-victims-include-loving-dad-sister-article-1.1534498|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 10, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT fatalities story\">{{cite news|last=Yee|first=Vivian|title=Man Going to Set Up Rockefeller Center Tree, a Nurse and a Paralegal Are Among the Dead|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/02/nyregion/accident-ends-commute-to-help-set-up-the-rockefeller-center-tree.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 10, 2013}}</ref>\n* James M. Ferrari, 59, of [[Montrose, New York|Montrose]]<ref name=\"NYT fatalities story\" />\n* James G. Lovell, 58, of [[Cold Spring, New York|Cold Spring]]<ref name=\"NYT fatalities story\" />\n* Donna L. Smith, 54, of [[Newburgh, New York|Newburgh]]\n}} only one was found inside the train after the derailment; the other three were thrown from the train as it derailed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wabc/story?section=news/local/new_york&id=9345353 |title=Metro-North victims: more than 60 injured, 4 killed &#124; 7online.com |publisher=WABC |date=December 2, 2013 |accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref> All had been sitting in the front three cars.<ref name=\"Daily News initial story\" />\n\n==Effects==\n\n===Response===\n\nThe [[New York City Fire Department]] sent over 125 firefighters to the scene to assist in the rescue. [[Emergency medical services|EMS]] workers were delayed getting to some victims while they waited for the third rails to be de-energized.<ref name=\"News 12 story\">{{cite news|title=Timeline of events from Metro-North train derailment near Spuyten Duyvil station|url=http://bronx.news12.com/news/timeline-of-events-from-metro-north-train-derailment-near-spuyten-duyvil-station-1.6525148|newspaper=[[News 12 Networks|News 12 The Bronx]]|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 8, 2013}}</ref> All service on the Hudson Line was suspended as a consequence of the accident.<ref name=Sky1176143>{{cite web |url=http://news.sky.com/story/1176143/four-people-killed-after-train-derails-in-new-york |title=Four People Killed After Train Derails In New York |publisher=Sky News |accessdate=December 1, 2013}}</ref> The nearby West Side Line was reopened to [[Amtrak]] trains by 3 p.m.<ref name=ABCNews21061304>{{cite web|title=Amtrak Trains From NYC to Albany Back in Service|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/amtrak-halts-nyc-albany-service-derailment-21061304|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=December 2, 2013}}</ref> Survivors were taken to a family resource center set up at nearby [[John F. Kennedy High School (New York City)|John F. Kennedy High School]]; after all passengers were accounted for, it was closed in the afternoon.<ref name=\"News 12 JFK high school story\">{{cite news|title=JFK High School in the Bronx set up as family relief center after Metro-North train derailment|url=http://bronx.news12.com/news/jfk-high-school-in-the-bronx-set-up-as-family-relief-center-after-metro-north-train-derailment-1.6521838|newspaper=News 12 The Bronx|date=December 1, 2013|accessdate=December 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Service and repairs===\n\nFor the day of the accident, Metro-North suspended all service on the Hudson Line south of [[Croton-Harmon (Metro-North station)|Croton-Harmon]]. The next day, the first regular business day back from the [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving]] holiday, it restored limited service as far south as [[Yonkers (Metro-North station)|Yonkers]], three stations north of where the derailment occurred, with shuttle buses providing service to the [[Van Cortlandt Park \u2013 242nd Street (IRT Broadway \u2013 Seventh Avenue Line)|Van Cortlandt Park\u2014242nd Street]] subway station, the northern terminus of the [[1 (New York City Subway service)|1]] train into Manhattan.<ref name=\"MTA post-accident service advisory\">{{cite web|title=MTA Service Status|url=http://new.mta.info/status/MetroNorth/Hudson/23100882|publisher=[[New York City Transit Authority|MTA]]|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref> Shuttle bus service was initiated between the [[Tarrytown (Metro-North station)|Tarrytown]] station on the Hudson Line and [[White Plains (Metro-North station)|White Plains]] on the Harlem Line.<ref name=\"Shuttle bus to Harlem Line\">{{cite news|title=Amtrak Service Restored in New York Following Metro-North Derailment|url=http://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/local/Amtrak-Service-Suspended-in-New-York-Following-Metro-North-Derailment-233990211.html|newspaper=[[Associated Press]]|date=December 1, 2013|accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref> [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] offered free parking for the duration of the disruption in the lot it operates at the [[Valhalla (Metro-North station)|Valhalla]] station north of [[White Plains, New York|White Plains]].<ref name=\"Rockland Times story\" />\n[[File:Spuyten Duyvil derailment site from Henry Hudson Bridge hill.jpg|thumb|left|Wreck scene late that afternoon|alt=An area of land with brown vegetation lit by golden late-afternoon sunlight next to water and railroad tracks in the background at the base of a steep hill with a white concrete retaining wall. A silvery rail car lies along the shore, almost all the way to the water, with its windows either broken out or severely cracked. Behind it is another car, lying almost on its side.]]\nMetro-North was not the only passenger railroad to experience service disruption. [[Amtrak]], whose [[Empire Service (train)|Empire Service]] trains follow the West Side Line tracks from the accident site to Penn Station, suspended all service between New York City and [[Albany-Rensselaer (Amtrak station)|Albany]] that day, stranding college students and others relying on the train to return to school after the holiday.<ref name=\"Amtrak suspension\">{{cite news|last=Cusma|first=Kathryn|last2=Harshbarger|first2=Rebecca|last3=Li|first3=David K.|title=Metro-North derailment causes massive service disruption|url=https://nypost.com/2013/12/01/metro-north-derailment-causes-massive-service-disruption/|newspaper=[[New York Post]]|date=December 1, 2013|accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref> By the afternoon it had been restored, with delays due to reduced speeds and activity in the accident area.<ref name=\"Amtrak restoration tweet\">{{cite web|title=UPDATE|url=https://twitter.com/Amtrak/statuses/407237056750833664|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=December 1, 2013|accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe next morning, many of the 26,000 who commute to the city via the Hudson Line were tolerant of the inconveniences and detours in stride. It was not the first time services had been disrupted; since it was the result of a fatal train wreck they put it in perspective. \"This is nothing; we have it great,\" said a receptionist as she sat on a bus. \"We're living like kings and queens\" compared to the grieving families of the dead. But some others said on future trips along the Hudson Line they would sit elsewhere in the train in case of another accident.<ref name=\"NYT commuter disruption story\">{{cite news|last1=Santora|first1=Marc|last2=Schweber|first2=Nate|title=After Fatal Crash, Metro-North Commuters Reflect on a Daily Routine|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/03/nyregion/after-fatal-crash-metro-north-commuters-reflect-on-a-daily-routine.html?src=recg|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSome commuters temporarily switched to buses, or drove themselves. Across the Hudson, [[Rockland County, New York|Rockland County]] offered extra express bus service across the [[Tappan Zee Bridge (1955\u20132017)|Tappan Zee Bridge]] to Tarrytown. Drivers noted a slight increase in traffic on the [[Saw Mill River Parkway]] as well.<ref name=\"Rockland Times story\" />\n[[File:Nighttime repair work after Spuyten Duyvil derailment.jpg|thumb|right|MTA crews working through the night to lay new track|alt=A crew of men in orange vests with reflector stripes and neon green hard hats over their clothing laying new railroad ties. Behind them is a large yellow piece of heavy equipment. It is night, and the scene is illuminated by large lights.]]\nMTA crews worked around the clock to remove the derailed cars and repair damage caused to the tracks when they left them. They spent the day after the crash replacing [[Track ballast|ballast]] and laying new [[concrete sleeper|concrete ties]]. By the evening of December 2 all the cars had been righted and restored to the track. They were taken to the Croton-Harmon and [[Highbridge Facility|Highbridge]] [[rail yard|yards]], where the NTSB impounded them for further investigations. Crews siphoned {{convert|900|gal}} of [[diesel fuel]] from the locomotive before removing it, then cleaned spilled fuel from the site with other special equipment.<ref name=\"Rockland Times story\" />\n\nLimited service on one of the three tracks of the Hudson Line through the accident site was restored on Wednesday morning, December 4. Separate trains were combined to make the service possible.<ref>[http://www.myfoxny.com/story/24130821/service-restored-to-affected-ny-train-line Service Restored] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206065711/http://www.myfoxny.com/story/24130821/service-restored-to-affected-ny-train-line |date=December 6, 2013 }} MyfoxNY</ref> Commuters waiting at Poughkeepsie on the first train to run the same route at the same time told a reporter that they were surprised that Metro-North was able to get the line cleared and the trains running again so quickly. Some even expressed sympathy for Rockefeller. While they said they had no fears of the accident recurring, and indeed some said it was safer than driving, one woman was surprised that there had been no fail-safe systems that could have prevented the derailment. \"I really thought they had that in place. This is the United States.\"<ref name=\"THR first trip story\">{{cite news|last=Nani|first=James|title=Derailment: Quiet and caution on the first full train ride since Sunday's accident|url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20131205/NEWS/131209870/-1/NEWS14|newspaper=Times Herald-Record|date=December 5, 2013|accessdate=December 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n\nThe derailment was the first accident involving passenger fatalities in Metro-North's 30-year history,<ref name=\"NYT investigation story\" /> and its first accident in New York involving any fatalities since a 1988 collision in [[Mount Vernon, New York|Mount Vernon]] that killed one crew member.<ref name=\"NYT19880414\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/04/14/nyregion/engineer-cited-in-metro-north-crash.html | title=Engineer Cited in Metro-North Crash | newspaper=New York Times | date=April 14, 1988 | accessdate=December 2, 2013 | author=Feron, James}}</ref> Two days later, [[Federal Railroad Administration]] (FRA) director Joseph Szabo sent MTA head Thomas Prendergast a letter highly critical of the transit agency. Earlier that year, he observed, there had been [[Fairfield train crash|a derailment]] on the [[New Haven Line]] serving Connecticut and Westchester County suburbs along [[Long Island Sound]], [[July 2013 Spuyten Duyvil derailment|a CSX freight derailment]] on the Hudson Line on the very next curve to the south of where the Spuyten Duyvil wreck had occurred,<ref name=\"NYT July derailment story\" /> on the other side of the Spuyten Duyvil station, and an accident on the New Haven Line that killed a track worker. These had led to five deaths and 129 injuries. \"The specific causes of each of these accidents may vary,\" Szabo wrote, \"but regardless of the reasons, four serious accidents in less than seven months is simply unacceptable.\"<ref name=\"FRA letter story\">{{cite news|last1=Keane|first1=Angela Greiling|last2=Klopott|first2=Freeman|last3=Goldman|first3=Henry|title=Metro-North Rebuked by U.S. Rail Regulator Over Accidents|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-12-04/metro-north-rebuked-by-u-s-rail-regulator-over-accidents.html|newspaper=[[Bloomberg news]]|date=December 3, 2013|accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSzabo asked the MTA for \"a serious, good faith commitment to the safe operation of the system.\" He said it needed to tell employees what, specifically, it would do to improve safety. He requested an answer in two days.<ref name=\"FRA letter story\" /> \"Immediate corrective action is imperative.\" Metro-North announced the day afterwards that it would institute a telephone line where employees could confidentially report \"close calls.\"<ref name=\"NYT alerter story\" /> Prendergast later replied to Szabo that the railroad had held mandatory safety discussions for 4,000 employees at 20 locations since the accident.<ref name=\"FRA mandate story\">{{cite news|last=Juva-Brown|first=Theresa|title=Metro-North ordered to have extra crew members in train cabs, new signals|url=http://www.lohud.com/article/20131206/NEWS/312060056/Metro-North-ordered-extra-crew-members-train-cabs-new-signals|newspaper=The Journal News|date=December 6, 2013|accessdate=December 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe accident spurred further discussion of [[positive train control]] (PTC), which might have prevented it. After a [[2008 Chatsworth train collision|2008 wreck]] in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], the FRA mandated all American railroads implement PTC by 2015. Many resisted, complaining about the cost of the technology. Among those railroads were both MTA commuter railroads, Metro-North and the [[Long Island Rail Road]], which have sought to have that deadline extended until 2018. In the wake of the Spuyten Duyvil derailment, U.S. Rep. [[Sean Patrick Maloney]], a resident of [[Cold Spring, New York|Cold Spring]] whose neighbor James Lovell was one of those killed, introduced legislation to make low-interest loans and guarantees available so that commuter railroads like Metro-North could implement PTC.<ref name=\"FRA letter story\" /> Eventually other congressmembers from the lower Hudson Valley joined as cosponsors.<ref name=\"Journal News Deep Dive story\">{{cite news|last=Juva-Brown|first=Theresa|title=Bronx derailment: Grants program pushed for Metro-North|url=http://www.lohud.com/article/20131215/NEWS/312150049/Bronx-derailment-Grants-program-pushed-Metro-North-|newspaper=[[The Journal News]]|date=December 15, 2013|accessdate=December 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Metro-North crew installing speed restriction sign.jpg|thumb|left|Metro-North crews install speed-restriction sign on a stretch of the [[New Haven Line]] two weeks after the Spuyten Duyvil accident|alt=Four men in reflectorized orange vests and neon green helmets standing next to a set of four railroad tracks installing a signpost next to the track. One is holding a sign with the letters \"SR\" in black on yellow. The ground, covered with a thin snow, slopes steeply to the left and an overhead gantry for the catenary is in the background.]]MTA officials denied that money was the problem, noting that they had budgeted $600 million of the total $900 million estimated cost of PTC installation. Instead they pointed to doubts about the technology's efficacy for large commuter rail networks. On a radio talk show following the crash, New York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] conceded that PTC is \"controversial ... [some people say] it's not what it's cracked up to be.\" The MTA itself said it was \"untested and unproven for commuter railroads [of our] size and complexity.\"<ref name=\"NYT alerter story\" />\n\nSeveral days later ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that the train had a device known as an [[cab signalling#Cab signalling in the United States|alerter]]. It sounds an alarm when the train exceeds speed limits for 25 seconds and shuts it down after an additional 15 seconds if no action is taken by the engineer. It might have been able to prevent the accident; however it was in the locomotive, at the rear of the train, not the cab where Rockefeller was located.<ref name=\"NYT alerter story\" />\n\nWhile Metro-North used it only to prevent collisions, rail safety experts said it could easily be configured to force trains to slow down at curves such as Spuyten Duyvil, since it relied on signals sent through the rails themselves. It was also preferable to the traditional [[dead man's switch]] the cab was equipped with, which requires constant action and attention from the engineer. The MTA said it was considering doing so at 30 sites on the Metro-North and LIRR networks.<ref name=\"NYT alerter story\" /> On December 6, the FRA issued an emergency order requiring Metro-North to have two qualified crew members in the cab at any point where the speed limit drops by more than {{convert|20|mph}} until it installs that technology in cabs and at those sites.<ref name=\"FRA mandate story\" /> The next day Metro-North announced it was upgrading the signals at the Spuyten Duyvil curve and several others in the system; it would also lower the speed limit going into the curve so that it would be a less-than-20-mph drop and thus the extra engineer would not be necessary.<ref name=\"MTA changes story\">{{cite news|title=Safety Upgrades Coming to Metro-North Derailment Site: MTA|url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Safety-Upgrades-MTA-Metro-North-Train-Derailment-Bronx-Spuyten-Duyvil-Curve-234987791.html|newspaper=[[WNBC-TV]]|date=December 8, 2013|accessdate=December 8, 2013}}</ref> U.S. Senators [[Richard Blumenthal]] of Connecticut and [[Charles Schumer]] of New York called on Metro-North to install cameras to monitor both the track and the engineers.<ref name=\"Senators call for cameras\">{{cite news|last=Castillo|first=Alfonso A.|title=Senators call for train cameras to monitor engineer, track|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/senators-call-for-train-cameras-to-monitor-engineer-track-1.6564959|newspaper=[[Newsday]]|date=December 8, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn December 12, the FRA went further. It ordered \"Operation Deep Dive,\"<ref name=\"Journal News Deep Dive story\" /> a full safety review of Metro-North, in which every aspect of its corporate culture would be evaluated by a panel of rail safety experts. This was the first time the agency had taken this extreme step since 2006, following a series of accidents involving [[CSX Transportation|CSX]] freights.<ref name=\"NYT full safety review story\">{{cite news|last=Flegenheimer|first=Matt|title=U.S. Orders Sweeping Safety Review of Metro-North|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/13/nyregion/us-orders-sweeping-safety-review-of-metro-north.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 13, 2013|accessdate=December 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-March 2014, the agency released its report to Congress on the results of Deep Dive. Metro-North, it said, had a \"deficient safety culture.\" The FRA identified \"three overarching safety concerns:\n* An overemphasis on on-time performance;\n* An ineffective Safety Department and poor safety culture; and \n* An ineffective training program.\"\nIt directed Metro-North to submit a plan for addressing these issues to it within 60 days. It was encouraged by the fact that many of the railroad's employees had cooperated thoroughly with investigators.<ref name=\"Deep Dive report\">[[Federal Railroad Administration]], {{cite web|url= http://www.fra.dot.gov/eLib/Details/L04952 |title=Operation Deep Drive: Metro-North Commuter Railroad Safety Assessment }}, March 2014, p. 11. Retrieved March 14, 2014</ref>\n\n===Investigation===\n[[File:Mike Flanigon inspects track (11170795505).jpg|thumb|NTSB investigators inspect the site of the derailment]]\nA team from the [[National Transportation Safety Board]] (NTSB) was dispatched to the scene of the accident to investigate.<ref name=BH011213/> It found that the train's brakes had been deployed seconds prior to the crash and that the tracks had no problems. From the [[train event recorder]]s, it determined that the train was traveling at {{convert|82|mph}}; the speed limit for the section of track involved is {{convert|30|mph}}.<ref>{{cite news|title=NTSB: Train traveling 82 mph approaching curve|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wabc/story?section=resources/traffic&id=9344996|newspaper=WABC|date=December 2, 2013}}</ref> The brakes had indeed been deployed, but had reached their maximum level five seconds after the train entered the curve.<ref name=\"Daily News initial story\">{{cite news|last1=Donohue|first1=Pete|last2=Lovett|first2=Kenneth|last3=Siemaszko|first3=Corky|title=Metro-North train was going 82 mph on a 30-mph curve before it derailed: Officials|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/metro-north-derailment-data-recorder-found-article-1.1534730|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter being lifted from where they had come to rest and restored to the track, the cars involved were impounded by the NTSB and taken to Metro-North's yards at [[Croton-Harmon (Metro-North station)|Croton-Harmon]] and [[Highbridge Facility|Highbridge]]. Rockefeller surrendered his cell phone and submitted samples for drug and alcohol tests. When it was reported that his attention had lapsed prior to the accident, investigators announced that they would be assembling a timeline of his 72 hours preceding the accident to see whether they could find any explanation.<ref name=\"Rockland Times story\" />\n\n===Cause===\n[[File:Spuyten Duyvil joint.jpg|thumb|right|A 2007 photo of the junction of the [[West Side Line]] (right) and the [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]], where the derailment took place|alt=Two railroad tracks curving in opposite directions in a brushy area with water on the right and a high bridge on the left. The track on that side has cement ties and a third rail; the one on the right has wooden ties. It goes to a bridge in the background on that side, behind which is a wooded hill.]]\nEarly reports suggested that Rockefeller had claimed the brakes failed,<ref name=\"first NY Post story\">{{cite news |last1=Celona |first1=Larry |last2=Schram |first2=Jamie |last3=Sheehan |first3=Kevin |title=4 dead, 63 injured in NYC train derail 'bloodbath' |url=https://nypost.com/2013/12/01/metro-north-train-derails-in-the-bronx/|date=December 1, 2013 |accessdate=December 10, 2013 |work=New York Post}}</ref> although experts pointed out that that was unlikely since the brakes were equipped with a [[fail safe]] device that activates them should it detect a pressure drop. The nearby freight derailment four months earlier<ref name=\"NYT July derailment story\">{{cite news |title=Metro-North Line Is Tied Up After a Freight Train Derails |date=July 19, 2013 |publisher=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/20/nyregion/train-derailment-on-metro-north-track-snarls-commute.html?|accessdate=December 10, 2013 |first1=Matt |last1=Flegenheimer |first2=Winnie |last2=Hu}}</ref> led to some early speculation that there was a problem with the track in the area.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe NTSB soon determined that there was no problem with the tracks or the signals. Rockefeller's blood tests came back negative for both alcohol and drugs; his cellphone similarly was out of use at the time of the accident. But, he admitted when investigators were able to interview him, he had drifted into a \"daze\" until just before the accident when he tried to stop at the last minute.<ref name=\"Pete Donohue column\">{{cite news|last=Donohue|first=Pete|title=Metro-North wreck: Engineer may have drifted off, but maybe management complacency set in, too|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/metro-north-wreck-engineer-drifted-management-complacency-set-article-1.1541636|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=December 8, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTwo days after the accident, Anthony Bottalico, head of the Association of Commuter Railroad Employees (ACRE), the Metro-North union, said that engineer William Rockefeller had \"nodded off\" before the accident. He likened it to [[Highway hypnosis|white-line fever]] experienced by truckers. Rockefeller had recently started working the early shift instead of in the afternoons; however on the day of the accident he had apparently had adequate sleep and arrived at work on time from his home in [[Germantown (town), New York|Germantown]], where he was seen to be alert and vivacious. Rockefeller's attorney confirmed the remarks. Shortly after Bottalico's comments, the NTSB barred ACRE from further participation in the investigation for disclosing too much information.<ref name=\"Politico union expulsion story\">{{cite news|last=Wolfe|first=Kathryn|title=Union ousted from train crash probe|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/12/union-ousted-from-metro-north-train-crash-probe-bronx-new-york-city-national-transportation-safety-board-100635.html?hp=f3|newspaper=[[Politico]]|date=December 3, 2013|accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref> A day later Rockefeller was [[Suspension (punishment)|suspended]] without pay.<ref name=\"Rockefeller suspension\">{{cite news|title=NYC train wreck engineer suspended without pay|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/nyc-train-wreck-engineer-suspended-without-pay/|newspaper=[[CBS News]]|date=December 5, 2013|accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn early April, federal investigators revealed that after the accident, Rockefeller had been diagnosed with severe [[obstructive sleep apnea]], a complication of his [[obesity]],<ref name=SF070414>{{cite web |url=http://www.standard-freeholder.com/2014/04/07/train-driver-in-fatal-ny-crash-had-sleep-disorder |title=Train driver in fatal N.Y. crash had sleep disorder |first=Jonathan |last=Allen |publisher=Reuters via Standard Freeholder |accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref> which may have contributed to his loss of attention. His blood had also been found to have a small amount of [[chlorpheniramine]], an [[Histamine antagonist|anti-histamine]] commonly found in [[Over-the-counter drug#United States|over-the-counter]] [[common cold|cold]] medications. Possible [[sedative]] effects require that those medications be [[Contraindication|contraindicated]] for use while driving or operating heavy machinery and include a warning to that effect on their packaging. While Rockefeller had initially denied taking any such medications to investigators, his lawyer said that would not justify a criminal charge, a step the district attorney's office said it was still considering at that point.<ref name=\"Daily News sleep apnea story\">{{cite news|last=Donohue|first=Pete|title=Metro-North engineer was on medication during crash, had sleep apnea: report|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/metro-north-engineer-sleep-disorder-meds-crash-article-1.1748476|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=April 7, 2014|accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:Weener Media Briefing (11188533193).jpg|thumb|NTSB Board Member Earl Weener briefs the press on the derailment]]\nThe NTSB's final report, issued almost 11 months after the accident, reiterated many of its earlier conclusions that [[positive train control]] would have prevented the accident by automatically applying the brakes in the curve, and that Rockefeller's sleep disorder was the likely reason for his loss of attention. It went on to fault Metro-North for not routinely screening for [[sleep disorder]]s employees in positions defined by federal regulations as safety-sensitive, and the FRA for not requiring railroads to do so. Lastly, it said that the failure of the [[Glazing (window)|glazings]], or the windows on the cars, contributed to the loss of life and severity of injury.<ref name=\"NTSB brief\" />\n\n===Legal actions===\n\n====Civil====\n\nWithin a week of the accident, attorneys for several passengers had filed notices of claims, the first step toward filing a lawsuit, against Metro-North. Lawyers for a police officer riding the train to work said his injuries could prevent him from returning to duty and demanded $10 million.<ref name=\"Russell lswsuit press release\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=N.Y.P.D. Cop Files $10 Million Claim For Metro North Derailment Injuries(Ronemus & Vilensky) |url=http://www.prunderground.com/n-y-p-d-cop-files-10-million-claim-for-metro-north-derailment-injuries-ronemus-vilensky/0029966/|publisher=PRUnderground.com |date=December 5, 2013 |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> In 2018 he settled for $450,000; his attorney said he had also been suffering [[post-traumatic stress disorder]] from the accident.<ref name=\"2018 lawsuit followup story\" /> Denise Williams, a dentist headed to a convention in the city who required back surgery for a [[Spinal fracture|fractured spine]] after she was trapped under a heavy passenger car for several hours, also gave notice through her attorney, who questioned among other things why the railroad had not replaced hundred-year-old track near the derailment site.<ref name=\"Williams suit story\">{{cite news|title=Lawsuit Planned On Behalf Of Woman Injured In Metro-North Derailment|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2013/12/03/lawsuit-planned-on-behalf-of-woman-injured-in-metro-north-derailment/|newspaper=[[WCBS-TV]]|date=December 3, 2013|accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nLawyers said it might be difficult for them to recover those amounts from Metro-North and the MTA if the cause of the accident turned out to be Rockefeller's lapse at the controls, since there would be far less [[civil liability|liability]] on their part. New York law further limits potential damages in cases like these. Victims' lawyers said their goal was not so much the money but making sure the railroad installed PTC.<ref name=\"Prosecution possibilities story\">{{cite news|last=Caruso|first=David|title=Prosecutors face tough choices in NYC derailment|url=https://news.yahoo.com/prosecutors-face-tough-choices-nyc-derailment-233300853.html|newspaper=[[Associated Press]]|date=December 5, 2013|accessdate=December 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn early April, after the release of the FRA report, a [[New Windsor, New York|New Windsor]] man who had been on the train filed suit. Eddie Russell named the MTA, Metro-North, the city and Rockefeller as defendants, seeking $10 million in [[punitive damages]]. \"One has to question whether the culture at Metro-North which led to the deaths of four people, should be investigated for criminal actions,\" said Russell's lawyer, who also faulted the MTA for not setting up a claims process in the wake of the accident, forcing those seeking compensation to litigate at increased costs both to themselves and the agencies.<ref name=\"THR lawsuit story\">{{cite news|last=Yakin|first=Heather|title=Injured New Windsor man files suit in derailment|url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20140408/NEWS/404080334|newspaper=[[Times-Herald Record]]|date=April 8, 2014|accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 it was reported that Metro-North had paid out $60 million in claims related to the accident, making it the costliest in the railroad's history. Since that amount exceeded the limit per accident in the MTA's [[liability insurance]], [[AIG]] was retained to cover its future legal costs, as not all the claims and litigation have been resolved yet.<ref name=\"2018 lawsuit followup story\" />\n\n=====Rockefeller lawsuit=====\n\nRockefeller, who retired on a full disability relating to sleep apnea, sued the MTA for $10 million for failing to install a system to alert engineers when the speed limit is exceeded.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zambito |first1=Thomas |last2=Fitz-Gibbon |first2=Jorge |date=December 2, 2016 |title=Derailment engineer $10M suit blames Metro-North |url=http://www.lohud.com/story/news/transit/2016/12/01/metro-north-derailment-engineer-sues/94733180/ |newspaper=The Journal News |access-date=December 10, 2016}}</ref> He argued that after another engineer had been [[suspension (punishment)|suspended]] for two weeks in 2005 after speeding through the same curve in a manner that knocked passengers' belongings off the overheard luggage rack, the railroad had to know the curve was dangerous; one of its engineers suggested installing the automatic braking. Metro-North's executives declined, the engineer had said, fearing it would add almost a minute to travel time.<ref name=\"Rockefeller lawsuit April 2018 story\">{{cite news|last=Zambito|first=Thomas C.|title=Exclusive: Former Metro-North engineer William Rockefeller's $10M lawsuit going to trial|url=https://www.lohud.com/story/news/2019/04/26/fatal-spuyten-duyvil-crash-lawsuit-against-metro-north-going-trial-william-rockefeller/3576462002/|newspaper=[[The Journal News]]|date=April 26, 2019|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter Metro-North had initially denied Rockefeller a disability pension based on the PTSD he suffered from the accident, he appealed, and in late 2016, Metro North announced that he would receive $3,200 a month. \"The Pension Disability Medical Review Board reviewed the appeal and determined that Mr. Rockefeller is disabled from performing his function as an engineer and he is eligible now to receive his pension,\" the MTA said. Rockefeller's lawyer declined to comment on the pension award but said the lawsuit would continue.<ref>{{cite news |last=Zambito |first=Thomas |date=December 23, 2016 |title=Metro-North engineer Rockefeller who dozed off gets lifetime pension |url=http://www.lohud.com/story/news/investigations/2016/12/23/metro-north-william-rockefeller-engineer-pension/95762964/ |newspaper=The Journal News |access-date=December 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe MTA [[countersuit|countersued]] Rockefeller for the same amount, citing the cost of the damage resulting from the accident. In April 2019 the federal judge hearing the case dismissed the MTA's motion for [[summary judgement]], ruling that Rockefeller had presented enough evidence that a juror could reasonably conclude his former employer was at fault. The railroad had in response introduced evidence from the train's event recorder that suggested Rockefeller had been driving the train erratically earlier on that run, at one point slowing to less than {{cvt|50|mph}} on a section where the speed limit was around {{cvt|70|mph}}, and had told Herbert when the train left Poughkeepsie that \"it's your job to keep me awake\", an account Herbert had denied making to prosecutors from the Bronx D.A.'s office during their investigation.<ref name=\"Rockefeller lawsuit April 2018 story\" />{{efn|Herbert said that was ridiculous as she could not have prevented Rockefeller from suffering a medical emergency and held him blameless in the crash. Her lawsuit against the MTA over her injuries from the accident, in which she had made the same argument as Rockefeller, was settled for $835,000 in 2015.<ref name=\"2018 lawsuit followup story\" />}} Four months later, Rockefeller withdrew the suit.<ref name=\"Riverdale Press story\">{{cite news|last=Hinman|first=Michael|title=Spuyten Duyvil crash engineer drops lawsuit|url=https://www.riverdalepress.com/stories/spuyten-duyvil-crash-engineer-drops-lawsuit,69819?|newspaper=The Riverdale News|date=August 25, 2019|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Criminal investigation====\n\nThe office of [[Bronx District Attorney]] [[Robert Johnson]] reviewed the evidence gathered to see whether criminal charges, which could be as serious as [[negligent homicide]], were warranted against Rockefeller.<ref name=\"Rockland Times story\" /> While criminal charges have been filed against the operators of vehicles in other recent deadly transportation accidents in and around New York City, and convictions have often resulted, defense lawyers said in this case it would be difficult to find a credible offense, since Rockefeller was exhibiting no clear sign of negligence such as alcoholism or cell phone use, and operating a vehicle while drowsy is not necessarily a crime. [[World Wide Tours bus crash#Prosecution of Ophadell Williams|In 2012]], prosecutors argued that Ophadell Williams, the driver of a bus on which 15 passengers died on their way to a casino in [[Connecticut]], had knowingly endangered lives by repeatedly driving without adequate sleep. A jury acquitted him of all charges except operating a vehicle without a [[driver's license|license]].<ref name=\"Prosecution possibilities story\" />\n\nIn May 2015, almost a year and a half after the accident, the Bronx D.A.'s office announced it would not be filing charges. \"There was no criminality in the act, therefore no criminal charges,\" said a spokeswoman for Johnson, adding that he had made that decision several months beforehand. Rockefeller's lawyer, Jeffrey Chartier, said that since his client hadn't known of his medical condition, he could not be considered to be negligent. It was \"the only logical conclusion\", similar to what the NTSB had already found.<ref name=\"Journal News no charges story\">{{cite news|last=Peltz|first=Jennifer|title=Bronx derailment: No charges for engineer in '13 crash|url=http://www.lohud.com/story/news/transit/2015/05/14/charges-engineer-william-rockefeller-caused-nyc-train-derailment-crash/27342575/|newspaper=[[The Journal News]]|date=May 15, 2015|accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nChartier said Rockefeller was still suffering from [[post-traumatic stress disorder]] (PTSD) as a result of the accident.<ref name=\"Journal News no charges story\" /> Smith, whose sister Donna died in the accident, accepted Johnson's decision, saying it spared her the stress of having to relive the accident at trial, stress [[2015 Philadelphia train derailment|a similar recent Amtrak accident]] was causing her at the time. She felt it was punishment enough for Rockefeller to have to live with his role in the accident. \"\"In a way, he's in jail forever, because he's got to live with this.\"<ref name=\"THR Linda Smith 2015 story\">{{cite news|last=Nani|first=James|title=Metro-North derailment victim's sister talks about decision not to criminally charge train's engineer|url=http://www.recordonline.com/article/20150515/NEWS/150519520/101008|newspaper=[[Times-Herald Record]]|date=May 16, 2015|accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Trains|New York City}}\n* [[List of American railroad accidents]]\n* [[List of rail accidents (2010\u2013present)]]\n\n===Similar accidents===\n* [[2015 Philadelphia train derailment]], later accident involving an Amtrak ''[[Northeast Regional]]'' train that sped in a 50&nbsp;mph curve more than twice that speed limit\n* [[2016 Hoboken train crash]], later accident involving New York City-area commuter rail where engineer was diagnosed with sleep apnea, possibly explaining why he lost awareness going into a station\n* [[2017 Washington train derailment]], also involving a train that went into a 30&nbsp;mph curve at more than twice that limit\n* [[Bourne End rail crash]], similar accident in Britain where a sleep-challenged engineer may have momentarily lost attention and taken the train into a curve too fast\n* [[Grantham rail crash]], another British accident with a similar momentary lapse of the engineer's attention suggested as an explanation for why he [[signal passed at danger|disregarded signals]] and derailed the train by taking it into a misaligned switch\n* [[Redondo Junction train wreck]], worst rail accident in Los Angeles history, where engineer who claimed to have \"blacked out\" before going into a curve too fast\n* [[Newton, Massachusetts, train collision]], in 2008, where the engineer's sleep apnea was also blamed posthumously for her inattention at a crucial moment\n* [[O'Hare station train crash]] in 2014; may also have been caused by an overworked, sleep-deprived train operator\n*[[2016 Croydon tram derailment]] a similar accident caused by a driver undergoing microsleep while in command of a tram.\n\n===Other Metro-North accidents===\n* [[Fairfield train crash]], May 2013\n* [[Valhalla train crash]], February 2015\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|December 2013 Spuyten Duyvil derailment}}\n* [http://app.ntsb.gov/investigations/2014/mnrsi/mnrsi.html#bronx2 Metro North Derailment - Bronx, NY] - NTSB\n* [http://app.ntsb.gov/doclib/reports/2014/RAB1412.pdf NTSB Railroad Accident Brief: Metro-North Railroad Derailment] - October 28, 2014\n\n{{2013 railway accidents}}\n\n[[Category:2013 in New York City]]\n[[Category:Derailments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving Metro-North Railroad]]\n[[Category:Railway accidents in 2013]]\n[[Category:Railway accidents and incidents in New York City]]\n[[Category:December 2013 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:21st century in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Spuyten Duyvil, Bronx]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Passenger commuter train accident that killed four}}\n{{about|the passenger train that derailed at Spuyten Duyvil in December 2013|the freight train that derailed nearby in July of the same year|July 2013 Spuyten Duyvil derailment}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Use American English|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox public transit accident\n| name                = Spuyten Duyvil derailment (December 2013)\n<!-- Image          -->\n| image               = NTSBSpuytenDuyvilDerailment2013.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| image_alt           = An aerial view of a wooded area between two watery areas in late autumn, with two railroad tracks forking to the top near the left and one following the water's edge. Several silvery train cars and a locomotive are lying on their sides off the tracks to the top; there are many parked yellow and white trucks and other vehicles between the two tracks.\n| caption             = Aerial view of the derailment\n<!-- Maps           -->\n| image_map           = \n| image_map_alt       = \n| image_map_caption   = \n| pushpin_map         = \n| alternative_map     = \n| pushpin_map_alt     = \n| pushpin_map_caption = \n| mapframe            = \n| qid                 = \n| mapframe_zoom       = \n| coordinates         = {{Coord|40.879597|N|73.922829|W|format=dms|type:event_region:US-NY_scale:50000|display=inline,title}}\n<!-- Details        -->\n| date                = December 1, 2013\n| time                = 7:19 a.m. [[Eastern Standard Time (North America)|EST]] (12:19 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]])\n| location            = Near [[Spuyten Duyvil (Metro-North station)|Spuyten Duyvil station]]\n| location_dir        = \n| location_city       = The Bronx, [[New York City|NY]]\n| location_dist_km    = \n| location_dist_mi    = \n| country             = United States\n| line                = [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]]\n| operator            = [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|MTA]], [[Metro-North Railroad]]\n| owner               = \n| service             = \n| type                = [[Derailment]]\n| cause               = Driver error, overspeeding\n<!-- Statistics     --> \n| bus                 = \n| trains              = 1\n| vehicles            = \n| passengers          = 115\n| crew                = \n| pedestrians         = \n| deaths              = 4\n| injuries            = At least 61\n| damage              = $9 million<ref name=\"NTSB brief\">{{cite web|title=Railroad Accident Brief: Metro-North Derailment|url=http://www.ntsb.gov/doclib/reports/2014/RAB1412.pdf|publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|date=October 24, 2014|accessdate=October 30, 2014}}</ref>\n| property            = \n<!-- Route map      -->\n| route_map           = \n| route_map_state     = \n| route_map_name      = \n<!-- Footnotes      --> \n| footnotes           = \n}}\nOn the morning of December 1, 2013, a [[Metro-North Railroad]] [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]] passenger train [[derailment|derailed]] near the [[Spuyten Duyvil (Metro-North station)|Spuyten Duyvil station]] in the [[New York City]] borough of [[the Bronx]]. Four of about 115 passengers were killed and another 61 injured; the accident caused $9 million worth of damage.<ref name=\"NTSB brief\" /> It was the deadliest [[train wreck|train accident]] within New York City since a [[1991 Union Square derailment|1991 subway derailment]] in lower [[Manhattan]],<ref name=\"wp\">{{cite news|first=Emily|last=Thibodeaux|title=Train derailment in New York City leaves four dead, dozens injured; NTSB investigating|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/nyc-train-derailment-leaves-4-dead-dozens-injured/2013/12/01/d180a0fe-5aa1-11e3-bf7e-f567ee61ae21_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=December 1, 2013|accessdate=December 6, 2013}}</ref> and the first accident in Metro-North's history to result in passenger fatalities.<ref name=\"NYT investigation story\">{{cite news|last1=Barron|first1=James|last2=Goodman|first2=J. David|title=Focus Turns to Investigation in Fatal Bronx Train Crash|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/02/nyregion/metro-north-derailment.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref> The additional $60 million in legal claims paid out {{as of|2020|lc=yes}} have also made it the costliest accident in Metro-North's history.<ref name=\"2018 lawsuit followup story\">{{cite news|last=Zambito|first=Thomas C.|title=Spuyten Duyvil derailment: Five years later - lawsuits, payouts and blame for Metro-North|url=https://www.lohud.com/story/news/investigations/2018/11/28/lawsuits-payouts-wake-2013-spuyten-duyvil-derailment/2060225002/|newspaper=[[The Journal News]]|date=November 28, 2018|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly investigations found that the train had gone into the curve where it derailed at almost three times the posted speed limit. The engineer, William Rockefeller, later admitted that before reaching the curve he had gone into a \"daze\", a sort of [[highway hypnosis]].\n\nThe leader of the [[National Transportation Safety Board]] (NTSB) team investigating said it was likely that the accident would have been prevented had [[positive train control]] (PTC) been installed per a prior federal mandate requiring its installation by 2015. Due to a number of other recent accidents involving Metro-North trains and tracks, the [[Federal Railroad Administration]] (FRA) demanded improved safety measures, which Metro-North began implementing within a week of the accident.\n\nIn late 2014, almost a year after the accident, the NTSB released its final report on the accident. After reiterating its earlier conclusion that PTC would have prevented the accident entirely, it found the most direct cause was Rockefeller's inattention as the train entered the curve. There were other contributing factors. A medical examination following the accident diagnosed [[sleep apnea]], which had hampered his ability to fully adjust his sleep patterns to the morning shift which he had begun working two weeks earlier. The report faulted both Metro-North for not screening its employees in sensitive positions for [[sleep disorder]]s, and the FRA for not requiring railroads to do such screening.<ref name=\"NTSB brief\" />\n\n=={{anchor|Train}}Background==\n\nThe train involved in the accident was the second southbound [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]] train of the day, leaving [[Poughkeepsie (Metro-North station)|Poughkeepsie]], the line's northern terminus, at its scheduled departure time of 5:54&nbsp;a.m. [[Eastern Standard Time (North America)|EST]].<ref name=\"current Metro-North schedule\">[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]], {{cite web|url= http://web.mta.info/mnr/html/planning/schedules/pdf/NOV172013HUD-SS.pdf |title=Hudson Line weekend schedule|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|date= November 17, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216041718/http://www.mta.info/mnr/html/planning/schedules/pdf/NOV172013HUD-SS.pdf|archivedate=December 16, 2013|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> It was powered by a [[GE Genesis|GE P32AC-DM]] [[dual-mode locomotive|locomotive]],<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript\">{{cite web|title=Transcript of Interview 8808 Engineer|url=http://dms.ntsb.gov/public%2F55500-55999%2F55841%2F551511.pdf|publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|page=48|date=December 3, 2013|accessdate=October 31, 2014}}</ref> capable of running on either diesel fuel or electricity from a [[third rail]]. Since Metro-North uses [[Push\u2013pull train#Locomotive at one end|push-pull trains]], it was situated at the northern, or rear, end of the train to minimize noise on the underground platforms at [[Grand Central Terminal]] in Manhattan, its final destination,<ref name=\"NYT alerter story\">{{cite news|last1=Flegenheimer|first1=Matt|last2=Fessenden|first2=Ford|last3=Fountain|first3=Henry|title=Train Had a Warning System, Just Not in the Operator's Cab|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/05/nyregion/as-metro-north-resumes-service-riders-get-back-to-routine.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 5, 2013|accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> where it was scheduled to arrive at 7:43.<ref name=\"current Metro-North schedule\" />  It carried about 115 passengers.<ref name=\"NTSB brief\" />\n[[File:Metro-North Shoreliner IV 6222.jpg|thumb|left|The lead train car involved in the derailment, pictured in 2009 leading a [[Harlem Line]] train into [[North White Plains (Metro-North station)|North White Plains]]|alt=A train headed by a light gray car with a red stripe on the side on a track between two others in a walled area moving from right to left across the image. On its front is the number 6222.]]\nEngineer William Rockefeller, a 15-year Metro-North veteran who had started as a clerk in the [[stationmaster]]'s office at Grand Central and then spent 10 years as an engineer, was operating the train from the [[cab car]], at the front of a [[wikt:consist#Noun|consist]] of seven [[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier]]-made [[Shoreliner]] passenger coaches,<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript\" /> in a mix of Metro-North and [[Connecticut Department of Transportation]] livery,{{efn|The two agencies share equipment for operation on the non-electrified [[Danbury Branch|Danbury]] and [[Waterbury Branch|Waterbury]] branches of the [[New Haven Line]].}} two of which were closed off and used only for [[Dead mileage#Deadheading|deadheading]] by employees.<ref name=\"Hermann interview transcript\">{{cite web|title=Transcript of Interview Conductor|url=http://dms.ntsb.gov/public%2F55500-55999%2F55841%2F551523.pdf|publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|page=36|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=November 1, 2014}}</ref> He had recently begun working the morning shift after working afternoons, a change he later told investigators he had made reluctantly,<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript 23\">''8808 Engineer'', 23.</ref> requiring that he leave his home in [[Germantown (town), New York|Germantown]], approximately {{convert|27|mi}} north of Poughkeepsie, at 3:30&nbsp;a.m. for work. To make sure he had adequate rest before his shift, he had gone to bed at 8:30&nbsp;p.m. the night before following a nine-hour shift the preceding day.<ref name=\"Rockland Times story\" /> He had arrived at work on time after a 43-minute drive, after which he bought a cup of coffee and a [[hard roll]], filled out paperwork and attended a standard safety briefing, followed by tests of the train's safety equipment.<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript 6\">''8808 Engineer'', 5-6</ref> Another veteran employee, Michael Hermann, who in his limited time working with Rockefeller had praised the engineer's \"very smooth\" train handling to other Metro-North employees,<ref name=\"Hermann interview transcript 50\">''Conductor'', 50.</ref> was the [[Conductor (transportation)#Conductors in North America|conductor]]; his one assistant leaving Poughkeepsie was Maria Herbert, with whom he regularly worked.<ref name=\"Hermann interview transcript 39-40\">''Conductor'', 39-40.</ref>\n\nOnce underway in predawn darkness that gradually lightened to [[civil twilight]],<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript 19\">''8808 Engineer'', 19</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=December 2013 \u2014 Sun in Poughkeepsie|url=https://www.timeanddate.com/sun/usa/poughkeepsie?month=12&year=2013|publisher=timeanddate.com|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> the train proceeded south along the two-track main line, also used by [[Amtrak]] for its [[Empire Service (train)|Empire Service]] trains. From Poughkeepsie it continued through the mid- and lower [[Hudson Valley]], often right next to  [[Hudson River|the river]]. Under [[electromotor]] diesel power, it made all six of its scheduled stops in the upper, non-electrified portion of the Hudson Line in [[Dutchess County, New York|Dutchess]], [[Putnam County, New York|Putnam]] and [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester]] counties without incident. After [[Croton-Harmon (Metro-North station)|Croton-Harmon]], the northern end of the line's [[Railway electrification system|electrification]], where it picked up another assistant conductor, Chris Kelly, it was held up briefly.<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript 7\">''8808 Engineer'', 7</ref> The next stop was [[Ossining (Metro-North station)|Ossining]], where it became an [[Express train|express]], continuing under diesel power.{{efn|Despite the presence of electrification, Metro-North's dual-mode trains use it only when they enter the [[Park Avenue Tunnel (railroad)|Park Avenue Tunnel]], since New York City bans the use of diesel locomotives in tunnels. Similar bans apply to the [[Long Island Rail Road]], where diesel trains must also be dual-mode.}} Between Ossining and the last stop, [[Tarrytown (Metro-North station)|Tarrytown]],<ref name=\"current Metro-North schedule\" /> just after dawn,<ref>{{cite web|title=December 2013 \u2014 Sun in Yonkers|url=https://www.timeanddate.com/sun/usa/yonkers?month=12&year=2013|publisher=timeanddate.com|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> Hermann and Herbert swept toward the center of the train, where they met briefly. After Tarrytown, with the train running only a minute behind schedule,<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript 34\">''8808 Engineer'', 34.</ref> they began returning to opposite ends of the train, taking seat checks from any passengers who might have boarded there. They were positioning themselves for where Metro-North's rules required them to be, so Herbert could join Rockefeller in the cab and call out signals after the last stop, [[Harlem\u2013125th Street (Metro-North station)|Harlem\u2013125th Street]]. Hermann, in the rear deadhead car with what he estimated to be six other employees, including Kelly, whom he had instructed to do so as the train's light passenger load did not require a third conductor, began doing his paperwork for the trip and preparing for his next.<ref name=\"Hermann interview transcript 39-40\" />\n\nThe train continued south over the next {{convert|14|mi}}<ref name=\"NTSB brief\" /> on a straight set of four tracks next to the river, all with third rails, past the four stations along the line in the city of [[Yonkers, New York|Yonkers]], a permanent speed restriction of {{convert|50|mph}} through downtown was augmented by a temporary {{cvt|60|mph|adj=on}} limit around [[Ludlow (Metro-North station)|Ludlow]] due to construction.<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript 8\">''8808 Engineer'', 8</ref> South of that station the train entered [[the Bronx]]. About {{convert|1.5|mi}} south of the [[Riverdale (Metro-North station)|Riverdale]] station, Rockefeller should have begun to slow the train down in anticipation of the curve<ref name=\"Daily News Harrod story\">{{cite news|last=Donohue|first=Pete|title='It looks bad for the engineer' of derailed Metro-North train: Safety pro|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/bad-engineer-derailed-train-pro-article-1.1535632|newspaper=[[New York Daily News]]|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 6, 2013}}</ref> immediately before [[Spuyten Duyvil (Metro-North station)|Spuyten Duyvil station]], below the [[Henry Hudson Bridge]] where the [[Harlem River Ship Canal]] flows into the Hudson across from the northern tip of Manhattan Island. Instead, he later said:\n{{quote|I [don]'t know how to explain it ... it was sort of like I was dazed, you know, looking straight ahead, almost like mesmerized. And I don't know if anybody's ever experienced like [[highway hypnosis|driving a long period of time in a car and staring at the taillights in front of them, and you get almost like that hypnotic feeling staring straight ahead]] ...  I was just staring straight ahead ... [it was] that hypnotized feeling, dazed, that's what I was [feeling].<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript 8\" />}}\n\nIt was interrupted when, he felt, \"something wasn't right with [the train].\"<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview transcript 8\" /> Linda Smith, of [[Newburgh (city), New York|Newburgh]], who had boarded the train at [[Beacon (Metro-North station)|Beacon]] with her sister Donna to see a choral performance at [[Lincoln Center]], recalled that although she, too, was not fully awake, something seemed wrong. \"It was bumpy and just seemed really at that point I was aware of going very fast.\"<ref name=\"THR survivor account\">{{cite news|last=Nani|first=James|title=Derailment: Sister lives with memory of tragic ride and loss of best friend Donna Smith|url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20131204/NEWS/312040324/-1/NEWS98|newspaper=[[Times Herald-Record]]|location=[[Middletown, Orange County, New York|Middletown, NY]]|date=December 4, 2013|accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> In the cab, Rockefeller initiated an emergency application of the brakes in an attempt to slow the train down, but it was already taking the curve.<ref name=\"Daily News Harrod story\" />\n\n==Accident==\n[[File:Spuyten Duyvil derailment site map.svg|right|thumb|Map of derailment site, with cars shown in red|alt=A map showing the accident site, with the cars depicted as red lines]]\nAt 7:19&nbsp;a.m. the train derailed {{convert|100|yd|m}} north of the Spuyten Duyvil station, {{convert|11.4|mi}} north of Grand Central,<ref name=\"NTSB brief\" /> just after it had passed the junction with the [[West Side Line]]'s crossing over the [[Spuyten Duyvil Bridge]], where Amtrak's trains split off to go to [[Penn Station (New York)|Penn Station]]. In her passenger car, Linda Smith recalled the train turning sideways as the bumps she had felt gave way to bounces and seat cushions flew through the air. \"It was like a movie going on around me.\"<ref name=\"THR survivor account\" /> Debris entered the cars through the broken windows.<ref name=\"Rockland Times story\">{{cite news|last=Demarest|first=Bill|title=Focus in Probe of Deadly Metro-North Derailment Turns to Engineer|url=http://www.rocklandtimes.com/2013/12/04/focus-in-probe-of-deadly-metro-north-derailment-turns-to-engineer/|newspaper=Rockland County Times|date=December 4, 2013|accessdate=December 6, 2013}}</ref> Joel Zaritsky, a dentist from [[LaGrangeville, New York|LaGrangeville]] headed to a convention, said it was like \"severe turbulence on an airplane.\"<ref name=\"PoJo survivor account\">{{cite news|last=Schutzman|first=Nina|title='I Realized I was Alive...' My story of the chaos when my Metro-North train flipped and crashed|url=http://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/article/20131208/NEWS01/312080054/metro-north-train-derailment|newspaper=[[Poughkeepsie Journal]]|date=December 8, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the rear deadhead car, Hermann first heard \"a little bit of like a metallic rattling,\" which was by itself not an unusual sound, but it just sounded a little bit odd.\" He recalled to investigators a day later that \"the next thing I know my car had kicked and I was thrown from the fourth seat or across the coach up to the ceiling ... I dropped down. I went back up again and I slammed into the ceiling and then I slammed down into the floor.\"<ref name=\"Conductor interview 9-11\">''Conductor'', 9\u201311</ref> In the front, Herbert was sitting in the passenger seat behind the cab when \"I looked up just to do what I was doing and a split second [later] I'm tumbling on the floor ... I think I hit the ceiling several times. I didn't even have time to react or to think what I was doing.\"<ref name=\"Herbert interview transcript\">{{cite web|title=Transcript of Interview Assistant Conductor 1|url=http://dms.ntsb.gov/public%2F55500-55999%2F55841%2F551517.pdf|publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|page=7|date=December 3, 2013|accessdate=November 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWhen the train came to rest, Hermann, despite a [[head injury]] and some bruises, took charge and reported the derailment to the dispatcher. He then worked with Kelly to coordinate the passengers and the emergency responders.<ref name=\"Conductor interview 9-11\" /> In the front Rockefeller, who was mostly uninjured, freed Herbert, who was conscious but had also suffered a head injury, from the seat cushions that had piled up on her. Seeing that Hermann and Kelley had taken charge of the situation, he remained with her until he was taken to a hospital to be examined.<ref name=\"Rockefeller interview 10-11\">''8808 Engineer'', 10\u201311</ref>\n\nAll seven cars and the locomotive left the tracks. Those in the rear remained next to the tracks; in the front, the cab came to rest just short of the Harlem River. Rockefeller, largely unhurt, got out and began aiding passengers. Trapped under seat cushions, Smith, too, was uninjured but unable to move; her sister was thrown from the train and was one of the four killed in the accident.<ref name=\"THR survivor account\" /> Linda Smith was one of the 61<ref name=\"NTSB brief\" /> injured.<ref name=BBC25176496>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-25176496 |title=New York train crash: Metro-North derailment in Bronx |publisher=BBC News Online |accessdate=December 1, 2013 |date=December 1, 2013}}</ref><ref name=BH011213>{{cite web |url=http://bostonherald.com/news_opinion/national/northeast/2013/12/governor_4_dead_63_hurt_in_nyc_train_derailment |title=Governor: 4 dead, 63 hurt in NYC train derailment |publisher=The Boston Herald |accessdate=December 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Fatalities ===\n\nOf the four killed,{{efn|\nThe four people killed were: \n* Kisook Ahn, 35, of [[Queens]]<ref name=\"Daily news victims story\">{{cite news|last1=Sit|first1=Ryan|last2=Scarborough|first2=Joey|last3=Moore|first3=Tina|title=Metro-North crash victims include loving dad, friendly roommate, 'inseparable' sister|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/metro-north-crash-victims-include-loving-dad-sister-article-1.1534498|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 10, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT fatalities story\">{{cite news|last=Yee|first=Vivian|title=Man Going to Set Up Rockefeller Center Tree, a Nurse and a Paralegal Are Among the Dead|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/02/nyregion/accident-ends-commute-to-help-set-up-the-rockefeller-center-tree.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 10, 2013}}</ref>\n* James M. Ferrari, 59, of [[Montrose, New York|Montrose]]<ref name=\"NYT fatalities story\" />\n* James G. Lovell, 58, of [[Cold Spring, New York|Cold Spring]]<ref name=\"NYT fatalities story\" />\n* Donna L. Smith, 54, of [[Newburgh, New York|Newburgh]]\n}} only one was found inside the train after the derailment; the other three were thrown from the train as it derailed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wabc/story?section=news/local/new_york&id=9345353 |title=Metro-North victims: more than 60 injured, 4 killed &#124; 7online.com |publisher=WABC |date=December 2, 2013 |accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref> All had been sitting in the front three cars.<ref name=\"Daily News initial story\" />\n\n==Effects==\n\n===Response===\n\nThe [[New York City Fire Department]] sent over 125 firefighters to the scene to assist in the rescue. [[Emergency medical services|EMS]] workers were delayed getting to some victims while they waited for the third rails to be de-energized.<ref name=\"News 12 story\">{{cite news|title=Timeline of events from Metro-North train derailment near Spuyten Duyvil station|url=http://bronx.news12.com/news/timeline-of-events-from-metro-north-train-derailment-near-spuyten-duyvil-station-1.6525148|newspaper=[[News 12 Networks|News 12 The Bronx]]|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 8, 2013}}</ref> All service on the Hudson Line was suspended as a consequence of the accident.<ref name=Sky1176143>{{cite web |url=http://news.sky.com/story/1176143/four-people-killed-after-train-derails-in-new-york |title=Four People Killed After Train Derails In New York |publisher=Sky News |accessdate=December 1, 2013}}</ref> The nearby West Side Line was reopened to [[Amtrak]] trains by 3 p.m.<ref name=ABCNews21061304>{{cite web|title=Amtrak Trains From NYC to Albany Back in Service|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/amtrak-halts-nyc-albany-service-derailment-21061304|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=December 2, 2013}}</ref> Survivors were taken to a family resource center set up at nearby [[John F. Kennedy High School (New York City)|John F. Kennedy High School]]; after all passengers were accounted for, it was closed in the afternoon.<ref name=\"News 12 JFK high school story\">{{cite news|title=JFK High School in the Bronx set up as family relief center after Metro-North train derailment|url=http://bronx.news12.com/news/jfk-high-school-in-the-bronx-set-up-as-family-relief-center-after-metro-north-train-derailment-1.6521838|newspaper=News 12 The Bronx|date=December 1, 2013|accessdate=December 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Service and repairs===\n\nFor the day of the accident, Metro-North suspended all service on the Hudson Line south of [[Croton-Harmon (Metro-North station)|Croton-Harmon]]. The next day, the first regular business day back from the [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving]] holiday, it restored limited service as far south as [[Yonkers (Metro-North station)|Yonkers]], three stations north of where the derailment occurred, with shuttle buses providing service to the [[Van Cortlandt Park \u2013 242nd Street (IRT Broadway \u2013 Seventh Avenue Line)|Van Cortlandt Park\u2014242nd Street]] subway station, the northern terminus of the [[1 (New York City Subway service)|1]] train into Manhattan.<ref name=\"MTA post-accident service advisory\">{{cite web|title=MTA Service Status|url=http://new.mta.info/status/MetroNorth/Hudson/23100882|publisher=[[New York City Transit Authority|MTA]]|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref> Shuttle bus service was initiated between the [[Tarrytown (Metro-North station)|Tarrytown]] station on the Hudson Line and [[White Plains (Metro-North station)|White Plains]] on the Harlem Line.<ref name=\"Shuttle bus to Harlem Line\">{{cite news|title=Amtrak Service Restored in New York Following Metro-North Derailment|url=http://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/local/Amtrak-Service-Suspended-in-New-York-Following-Metro-North-Derailment-233990211.html|newspaper=[[Associated Press]]|date=December 1, 2013|accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref> [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] offered free parking for the duration of the disruption in the lot it operates at the [[Valhalla (Metro-North station)|Valhalla]] station north of [[White Plains, New York|White Plains]].<ref name=\"Rockland Times story\" />\n[[File:Spuyten Duyvil derailment site from Henry Hudson Bridge hill.jpg|thumb|left|Wreck scene late that afternoon|alt=An area of land with brown vegetation lit by golden late-afternoon sunlight next to water and railroad tracks in the background at the base of a steep hill with a white concrete retaining wall. A silvery rail car lies along the shore, almost all the way to the water, with its windows either broken out or severely cracked. Behind it is another car, lying almost on its side.]]\nMetro-North was not the only passenger railroad to experience service disruption. [[Amtrak]], whose [[Empire Service (train)|Empire Service]] trains follow the West Side Line tracks from the accident site to Penn Station, suspended all service between New York City and [[Albany-Rensselaer (Amtrak station)|Albany]] that day, stranding college students and others relying on the train to return to school after the holiday.<ref name=\"Amtrak suspension\">{{cite news|last=Cusma|first=Kathryn|last2=Harshbarger|first2=Rebecca|last3=Li|first3=David K.|title=Metro-North derailment causes massive service disruption|url=https://nypost.com/2013/12/01/metro-north-derailment-causes-massive-service-disruption/|newspaper=[[New York Post]]|date=December 1, 2013|accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref> By the afternoon it had been restored, with delays due to reduced speeds and activity in the accident area.<ref name=\"Amtrak restoration tweet\">{{cite web|title=UPDATE|url=https://twitter.com/Amtrak/statuses/407237056750833664|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=December 1, 2013|accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe next morning, many of the 26,000 who commute to the city via the Hudson Line were tolerant of the inconveniences and detours in stride. It was not the first time services had been disrupted; since it was the result of a fatal train wreck they put it in perspective. \"This is nothing; we have it great,\" said a receptionist as she sat on a bus. \"We're living like kings and queens\" compared to the grieving families of the dead. But some others said on future trips along the Hudson Line they would sit elsewhere in the train in case of another accident.<ref name=\"NYT commuter disruption story\">{{cite news|last1=Santora|first1=Marc|last2=Schweber|first2=Nate|title=After Fatal Crash, Metro-North Commuters Reflect on a Daily Routine|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/03/nyregion/after-fatal-crash-metro-north-commuters-reflect-on-a-daily-routine.html?src=recg|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSome commuters temporarily switched to buses, or drove themselves. Across the Hudson, [[Rockland County, New York|Rockland County]] offered extra express bus service across the [[Tappan Zee Bridge (1955\u20132017)|Tappan Zee Bridge]] to Tarrytown. Drivers noted a slight increase in traffic on the [[Saw Mill River Parkway]] as well.<ref name=\"Rockland Times story\" />\n[[File:Nighttime repair work after Spuyten Duyvil derailment.jpg|thumb|right|MTA crews working through the night to lay new track|alt=A crew of men in orange vests with reflector stripes and neon green hard hats over their clothing laying new railroad ties. Behind them is a large yellow piece of heavy equipment. It is night, and the scene is illuminated by large lights.]]\nMTA crews worked around the clock to remove the derailed cars and repair damage caused to the tracks when they left them. They spent the day after the crash replacing [[Track ballast|ballast]] and laying new [[concrete sleeper|concrete ties]]. By the evening of December 2 all the cars had been righted and restored to the track. They were taken to the Croton-Harmon and [[Highbridge Facility|Highbridge]] [[rail yard|yards]], where the NTSB impounded them for further investigations. Crews siphoned {{convert|900|gal}} of [[diesel fuel]] from the locomotive before removing it, then cleaned spilled fuel from the site with other special equipment.<ref name=\"Rockland Times story\" />\n\nLimited service on one of the three tracks of the Hudson Line through the accident site was restored on Wednesday morning, December 4. Separate trains were combined to make the service possible.<ref>[http://www.myfoxny.com/story/24130821/service-restored-to-affected-ny-train-line Service Restored] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206065711/http://www.myfoxny.com/story/24130821/service-restored-to-affected-ny-train-line |date=December 6, 2013 }} MyfoxNY</ref> Commuters waiting at Poughkeepsie on the first train to run the same route at the same time told a reporter that they were surprised that Metro-North was able to get the line cleared and the trains running again so quickly. Some even expressed sympathy for Rockefeller. While they said they had no fears of the accident recurring, and indeed some said it was safer than driving, one woman was surprised that there had been no fail-safe systems that could have prevented the derailment. \"I really thought they had that in place. This is the United States.\"<ref name=\"THR first trip story\">{{cite news|last=Nani|first=James|title=Derailment: Quiet and caution on the first full train ride since Sunday's accident|url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20131205/NEWS/131209870/-1/NEWS14|newspaper=Times Herald-Record|date=December 5, 2013|accessdate=December 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n\nThe derailment was the first accident involving passenger fatalities in Metro-North's 30-year history,<ref name=\"NYT investigation story\" /> and its first accident in New York involving any fatalities since a 1988 collision in [[Mount Vernon, New York|Mount Vernon]] that killed one crew member.<ref name=\"NYT19880414\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/04/14/nyregion/engineer-cited-in-metro-north-crash.html | title=Engineer Cited in Metro-North Crash | newspaper=New York Times | date=April 14, 1988 | accessdate=December 2, 2013 | author=Feron, James}}</ref> Two days later, [[Federal Railroad Administration]] (FRA) director Joseph Szabo sent MTA head Thomas Prendergast a letter highly critical of the transit agency. Earlier that year, he observed, there had been [[Fairfield train crash|a derailment]] on the [[New Haven Line]] serving Connecticut and Westchester County suburbs along [[Long Island Sound]], [[July 2013 Spuyten Duyvil derailment|a CSX freight derailment]] on the Hudson Line on the very next curve to the south of where the Spuyten Duyvil wreck had occurred,<ref name=\"NYT July derailment story\" /> on the other side of the Spuyten Duyvil station, and an accident on the New Haven Line that killed a track worker. These had led to five deaths and 129 injuries. \"The specific causes of each of these accidents may vary,\" Szabo wrote, \"but regardless of the reasons, four serious accidents in less than seven months is simply unacceptable.\"<ref name=\"FRA letter story\">{{cite news|last1=Keane|first1=Angela Greiling|last2=Klopott|first2=Freeman|last3=Goldman|first3=Henry|title=Metro-North Rebuked by U.S. Rail Regulator Over Accidents|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-12-04/metro-north-rebuked-by-u-s-rail-regulator-over-accidents.html|newspaper=[[Bloomberg news]]|date=December 3, 2013|accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSzabo asked the MTA for \"a serious, good faith commitment to the safe operation of the system.\" He said it needed to tell employees what, specifically, it would do to improve safety. He requested an answer in two days.<ref name=\"FRA letter story\" /> \"Immediate corrective action is imperative.\" Metro-North announced the day afterwards that it would institute a telephone line where employees could confidentially report \"close calls.\"<ref name=\"NYT alerter story\" /> Prendergast later replied to Szabo that the railroad had held mandatory safety discussions for 4,000 employees at 20 locations since the accident.<ref name=\"FRA mandate story\">{{cite news|last=Juva-Brown|first=Theresa|title=Metro-North ordered to have extra crew members in train cabs, new signals|url=http://www.lohud.com/article/20131206/NEWS/312060056/Metro-North-ordered-extra-crew-members-train-cabs-new-signals|newspaper=The Journal News|date=December 6, 2013|accessdate=December 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe accident spurred further discussion of [[positive train control]] (PTC), which might have prevented it. After a [[2008 Chatsworth train collision|2008 wreck]] in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], the FRA mandated all American railroads implement PTC by 2015. Many resisted, complaining about the cost of the technology. Among those railroads were both MTA commuter railroads, Metro-North and the [[Long Island Rail Road]], which have sought to have that deadline extended until 2018. In the wake of the Spuyten Duyvil derailment, U.S. Rep. [[Sean Patrick Maloney]], a resident of [[Cold Spring, New York|Cold Spring]] whose neighbor James Lovell was one of those killed, introduced legislation to make low-interest loans and guarantees available so that commuter railroads like Metro-North could implement PTC.<ref name=\"FRA letter story\" /> Eventually other congressmembers from the lower Hudson Valley joined as cosponsors.<ref name=\"Journal News Deep Dive story\">{{cite news|last=Juva-Brown|first=Theresa|title=Bronx derailment: Grants program pushed for Metro-North|url=http://www.lohud.com/article/20131215/NEWS/312150049/Bronx-derailment-Grants-program-pushed-Metro-North-|newspaper=[[The Journal News]]|date=December 15, 2013|accessdate=December 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Metro-North crew installing speed restriction sign.jpg|thumb|left|Metro-North crews install speed-restriction sign on a stretch of the [[New Haven Line]] two weeks after the Spuyten Duyvil accident|alt=Four men in reflectorized orange vests and neon green helmets standing next to a set of four railroad tracks installing a signpost next to the track. One is holding a sign with the letters \"SR\" in black on yellow. The ground, covered with a thin snow, slopes steeply to the left and an overhead gantry for the catenary is in the background.]]MTA officials denied that money was the problem, noting that they had budgeted $600 million of the total $900 million estimated cost of PTC installation. Instead they pointed to doubts about the technology's efficacy for large commuter rail networks. On a radio talk show following the crash, New York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] conceded that PTC is \"controversial ... [some people say] it's not what it's cracked up to be.\" The MTA itself said it was \"untested and unproven for commuter railroads [of our] size and complexity.\"<ref name=\"NYT alerter story\" />\n\nSeveral days later ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that the train had a device known as an [[cab signalling#Cab signalling in the United States|alerter]]. It sounds an alarm when the train exceeds speed limits for 25 seconds and shuts it down after an additional 15 seconds if no action is taken by the engineer. It might have been able to prevent the accident; however it was in the locomotive, at the rear of the train, not the cab where Rockefeller was located.<ref name=\"NYT alerter story\" />\n\nWhile Metro-North used it only to prevent collisions, rail safety experts said it could easily be configured to force trains to slow down at curves such as Spuyten Duyvil, since it relied on signals sent through the rails themselves. It was also preferable to the traditional [[dead man's switch]] the cab was equipped with, which requires constant action and attention from the engineer. The MTA said it was considering doing so at 30 sites on the Metro-North and LIRR networks.<ref name=\"NYT alerter story\" /> On December 6, the FRA issued an emergency order requiring Metro-North to have two qualified crew members in the cab at any point where the speed limit drops by more than {{convert|20|mph}} until it installs that technology in cabs and at those sites.<ref name=\"FRA mandate story\" /> The next day Metro-North announced it was upgrading the signals at the Spuyten Duyvil curve and several others in the system; it would also lower the speed limit going into the curve so that it would be a less-than-20-mph drop and thus the extra engineer would not be necessary.<ref name=\"MTA changes story\">{{cite news|title=Safety Upgrades Coming to Metro-North Derailment Site: MTA|url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Safety-Upgrades-MTA-Metro-North-Train-Derailment-Bronx-Spuyten-Duyvil-Curve-234987791.html|newspaper=[[WNBC-TV]]|date=December 8, 2013|accessdate=December 8, 2013}}</ref> U.S. Senators [[Richard Blumenthal]] of Connecticut and [[Charles Schumer]] of New York called on Metro-North to install cameras to monitor both the track and the engineers.<ref name=\"Senators call for cameras\">{{cite news|last=Castillo|first=Alfonso A.|title=Senators call for train cameras to monitor engineer, track|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/senators-call-for-train-cameras-to-monitor-engineer-track-1.6564959|newspaper=[[Newsday]]|date=December 8, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn December 12, the FRA went further. It ordered \"Operation Deep Dive,\"<ref name=\"Journal News Deep Dive story\" /> a full safety review of Metro-North, in which every aspect of its corporate culture would be evaluated by a panel of rail safety experts. This was the first time the agency had taken this extreme step since 2006, following a series of accidents involving [[CSX Transportation|CSX]] freights.<ref name=\"NYT full safety review story\">{{cite news|last=Flegenheimer|first=Matt|title=U.S. Orders Sweeping Safety Review of Metro-North|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/13/nyregion/us-orders-sweeping-safety-review-of-metro-north.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 13, 2013|accessdate=December 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-March 2014, the agency released its report to Congress on the results of Deep Dive. Metro-North, it said, had a \"deficient safety culture.\" The FRA identified \"three overarching safety concerns:\n* An overemphasis on on-time performance;\n* An ineffective Safety Department and poor safety culture; and \n* An ineffective training program.\"\nIt directed Metro-North to submit a plan for addressing these issues to it within 60 days. It was encouraged by the fact that many of the railroad's employees had cooperated thoroughly with investigators.<ref name=\"Deep Dive report\">[[Federal Railroad Administration]], {{cite web|url= http://www.fra.dot.gov/eLib/Details/L04952 |title=Operation Deep Drive: Metro-North Commuter Railroad Safety Assessment }}, March 2014, p. 11. Retrieved March 14, 2014</ref>\n\n===Investigation===\n[[File:Mike Flanigon inspects track (11170795505).jpg|thumb|NTSB investigators inspect the site of the derailment]]\nA team from the [[National Transportation Safety Board]] (NTSB) was dispatched to the scene of the accident to investigate.<ref name=BH011213/> It found that the train's brakes had been deployed seconds prior to the crash and that the tracks had no problems. From the [[train event recorder]]s, it determined that the train was traveling at {{convert|82|mph}}; the speed limit for the section of track involved is {{convert|30|mph}}.<ref>{{cite news|title=NTSB: Train traveling 82 mph approaching curve|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wabc/story?section=resources/traffic&id=9344996|newspaper=WABC|date=December 2, 2013}}</ref> The brakes had indeed been deployed, but had reached their maximum level five seconds after the train entered the curve.<ref name=\"Daily News initial story\">{{cite news|last1=Donohue|first1=Pete|last2=Lovett|first2=Kenneth|last3=Siemaszko|first3=Corky|title=Metro-North train was going 82 mph on a 30-mph curve before it derailed: Officials|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/metro-north-derailment-data-recorder-found-article-1.1534730|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter being lifted from where they had come to rest and restored to the track, the cars involved were impounded by the NTSB and taken to Metro-North's yards at [[Croton-Harmon (Metro-North station)|Croton-Harmon]] and [[Highbridge Facility|Highbridge]]. Rockefeller surrendered his cell phone and submitted samples for drug and alcohol tests. When it was reported that his attention had lapsed prior to the accident, investigators announced that they would be assembling a timeline of his 72 hours preceding the accident to see whether they could find any explanation.<ref name=\"Rockland Times story\" />\n\n===Cause===\n[[File:Spuyten Duyvil joint.jpg|thumb|right|A 2007 photo of the junction of the [[West Side Line]] (right) and the [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]], where the derailment took place|alt=Two railroad tracks curving in opposite directions in a brushy area with water on the right and a high bridge on the left. The track on that side has cement ties and a third rail; the one on the right has wooden ties. It goes to a bridge in the background on that side, behind which is a wooded hill.]]\nEarly reports suggested that Rockefeller had claimed the brakes failed,<ref name=\"first NY Post story\">{{cite news |last1=Celona |first1=Larry |last2=Schram |first2=Jamie |last3=Sheehan |first3=Kevin |title=4 dead, 63 injured in NYC train derail 'bloodbath' |url=https://nypost.com/2013/12/01/metro-north-train-derails-in-the-bronx/|date=December 1, 2013 |accessdate=December 10, 2013 |work=New York Post}}</ref> although experts pointed out that that was unlikely since the brakes were equipped with a [[fail safe]] device that activates them should it detect a pressure drop. The nearby freight derailment four months earlier<ref name=\"NYT July derailment story\">{{cite news |title=Metro-North Line Is Tied Up After a Freight Train Derails |date=July 19, 2013 |publisher=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/20/nyregion/train-derailment-on-metro-north-track-snarls-commute.html?|accessdate=December 10, 2013 |first1=Matt |last1=Flegenheimer |first2=Winnie |last2=Hu}}</ref> led to some early speculation that there was a problem with the track in the area.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe NTSB soon determined that there was no problem with the tracks or the signals. Rockefeller's blood tests came back negative for both alcohol and drugs; his cellphone similarly was out of use at the time of the accident. But, he admitted when investigators were able to interview him, he had drifted into a \"daze\" until just before the accident when he tried to stop at the last minute.<ref name=\"Pete Donohue column\">{{cite news|last=Donohue|first=Pete|title=Metro-North wreck: Engineer may have drifted off, but maybe management complacency set in, too|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/metro-north-wreck-engineer-drifted-management-complacency-set-article-1.1541636|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=December 8, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTwo days after the accident, Anthony Bottalico, head of the Association of Commuter Railroad Employees (ACRE), the Metro-North union, said that engineer William Rockefeller had \"nodded off\" before the accident. He likened it to [[Highway hypnosis|white-line fever]] experienced by truckers. Rockefeller had recently started working the early shift instead of in the afternoons; however on the day of the accident he had apparently had adequate sleep and arrived at work on time from his home in [[Germantown (town), New York|Germantown]], where he was seen to be alert and vivacious. Rockefeller's attorney confirmed the remarks. Shortly after Bottalico's comments, the NTSB barred ACRE from further participation in the investigation for disclosing too much information.<ref name=\"Politico union expulsion story\">{{cite news|last=Wolfe|first=Kathryn|title=Union ousted from train crash probe|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/12/union-ousted-from-metro-north-train-crash-probe-bronx-new-york-city-national-transportation-safety-board-100635.html?hp=f3|newspaper=[[Politico]]|date=December 3, 2013|accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref> A day later Rockefeller was [[Suspension (punishment)|suspended]] without pay.<ref name=\"Rockefeller suspension\">{{cite news|title=NYC train wreck engineer suspended without pay|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/nyc-train-wreck-engineer-suspended-without-pay/|newspaper=[[CBS News]]|date=December 5, 2013|accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn early April, federal investigators revealed that after the accident, Rockefeller had been diagnosed with severe [[obstructive sleep apnea]], a complication of his [[obesity]],<ref name=SF070414>{{cite web |url=http://www.standard-freeholder.com/2014/04/07/train-driver-in-fatal-ny-crash-had-sleep-disorder |title=Train driver in fatal N.Y. crash had sleep disorder |first=Jonathan |last=Allen |publisher=Reuters via Standard Freeholder |accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref> which may have contributed to his loss of attention. His blood had also been found to have a small amount of [[chlorpheniramine]], an [[Histamine antagonist|anti-histamine]] commonly found in [[Over-the-counter drug#United States|over-the-counter]] [[common cold|cold]] medications. Possible [[sedative]] effects require that those medications be [[Contraindication|contraindicated]] for use while driving or operating heavy machinery and include a warning to that effect on their packaging. While Rockefeller had initially denied taking any such medications to investigators, his lawyer said that would not justify a criminal charge, a step the district attorney's office said it was still considering at that point.<ref name=\"Daily News sleep apnea story\">{{cite news|last=Donohue|first=Pete|title=Metro-North engineer was on medication during crash, had sleep apnea: report|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/metro-north-engineer-sleep-disorder-meds-crash-article-1.1748476|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=April 7, 2014|accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:Weener Media Briefing (11188533193).jpg|thumb|NTSB Board Member Earl Weener briefs the press on the derailment]]\nThe NTSB's final report, issued almost 11 months after the accident, reiterated many of its earlier conclusions that [[positive train control]] would have prevented the accident by automatically applying the brakes in the curve, and that Rockefeller's sleep disorder was the likely reason for his loss of attention. It went on to fault Metro-North for not routinely screening for [[sleep disorder]]s employees in positions defined by federal regulations as safety-sensitive, and the FRA for not requiring railroads to do so. Lastly, it said that the failure of the [[Glazing (window)|glazings]], or the windows on the cars, contributed to the loss of life and severity of injury.<ref name=\"NTSB brief\" />\n\n===Legal actions===\n\n====Civil====\n\nWithin a week of the accident, attorneys for several passengers had filed notices of claims, the first step toward filing a lawsuit, against Metro-North. Lawyers for a police officer riding the train to work said his injuries could prevent him from returning to duty and demanded $10 million.<ref name=\"Russell lswsuit press release\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=N.Y.P.D. Cop Files $10 Million Claim For Metro North Derailment Injuries(Ronemus & Vilensky) |url=http://www.prunderground.com/n-y-p-d-cop-files-10-million-claim-for-metro-north-derailment-injuries-ronemus-vilensky/0029966/|publisher=PRUnderground.com |date=December 5, 2013 |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> In 2018 he settled for $450,000; his attorney said he had also been suffering [[post-traumatic stress disorder]] from the accident.<ref name=\"2018 lawsuit followup story\" /> Denise Williams, a dentist headed to a convention in the city who required back surgery for a [[Spinal fracture|fractured spine]] after she was trapped under a heavy passenger car for several hours, also gave notice through her attorney, who questioned among other things why the railroad had not replaced hundred-year-old track near the derailment site.<ref name=\"Williams suit story\">{{cite news|title=Lawsuit Planned On Behalf Of Woman Injured In Metro-North Derailment|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2013/12/03/lawsuit-planned-on-behalf-of-woman-injured-in-metro-north-derailment/|newspaper=[[WCBS-TV]]|date=December 3, 2013|accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nLawyers said it might be difficult for them to recover those amounts from Metro-North and the MTA if the cause of the accident turned out to be Rockefeller's lapse at the controls, since there would be far less [[civil liability|liability]] on their part. New York law further limits potential damages in cases like these. Victims' lawyers said their goal was not so much the money but making sure the railroad installed PTC.<ref name=\"Prosecution possibilities story\">{{cite news|last=Caruso|first=David|title=Prosecutors face tough choices in NYC derailment|url=https://news.yahoo.com/prosecutors-face-tough-choices-nyc-derailment-233300853.html|newspaper=[[Associated Press]]|date=December 5, 2013|accessdate=December 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn early April, after the release of the FRA report, a [[New Windsor, New York|New Windsor]] man who had been on the train filed suit. Eddie Russell named the MTA, Metro-North, the city and Rockefeller as defendants, seeking $10 million in [[punitive damages]]. \"One has to question whether the culture at Metro-North which led to the deaths of four people, should be investigated for criminal actions,\" said Russell's lawyer, who also faulted the MTA for not setting up a claims process in the wake of the accident, forcing those seeking compensation to litigate at increased costs both to themselves and the agencies.<ref name=\"THR lawsuit story\">{{cite news|last=Yakin|first=Heather|title=Injured New Windsor man files suit in derailment|url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20140408/NEWS/404080334|newspaper=[[Times-Herald Record]]|date=April 8, 2014|accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 it was reported that Metro-North had paid out $60 million in claims related to the accident, making it the costliest in the railroad's history. Since that amount exceeded the limit per accident in the MTA's [[liability insurance]], [[AIG]] was retained to cover its future legal costs, as not all the claims and litigation have been resolved yet.<ref name=\"2018 lawsuit followup story\" />\n\n=====Rockefeller lawsuit=====\n\nRockefeller, who retired on a full disability relating to sleep apnea, sued the MTA for $10 million for failing to install a system to alert engineers when the speed limit is exceeded.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zambito |first1=Thomas |last2=Fitz-Gibbon |first2=Jorge |date=December 2, 2016 |title=Derailment engineer $10M suit blames Metro-North |url=http://www.lohud.com/story/news/transit/2016/12/01/metro-north-derailment-engineer-sues/94733180/ |newspaper=The Journal News |access-date=December 10, 2016}}</ref> He argued that after another engineer had been [[suspension (punishment)|suspended]] for two weeks in 2005 after speeding through the same curve in a manner that knocked passengers' belongings off the overheard luggage rack, the railroad had to know the curve was dangerous; one of its engineers suggested installing the automatic braking. Metro-North's executives declined, the engineer had said, fearing it would add almost a minute to travel time.<ref name=\"Rockefeller lawsuit April 2018 story\">{{cite news|last=Zambito|first=Thomas C.|title=Exclusive: Former Metro-North engineer William Rockefeller's $10M lawsuit going to trial|url=https://www.lohud.com/story/news/2019/04/26/fatal-spuyten-duyvil-crash-lawsuit-against-metro-north-going-trial-william-rockefeller/3576462002/|newspaper=[[The Journal News]]|date=April 26, 2019|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter Metro-North had initially denied Rockefeller a disability pension based on the PTSD he suffered from the accident, he appealed, and in late 2016, Metro North announced that he would receive $3,200 a month. \"The Pension Disability Medical Review Board reviewed the appeal and determined that Mr. Rockefeller is disabled from performing his function as an engineer and he is eligible now to receive his pension,\" the MTA said. Rockefeller's lawyer declined to comment on the pension award but said the lawsuit would continue.<ref>{{cite news |last=Zambito |first=Thomas |date=December 23, 2016 |title=Metro-North engineer Rockefeller who dozed off gets lifetime pension |url=http://www.lohud.com/story/news/investigations/2016/12/23/metro-north-william-rockefeller-engineer-pension/95762964/ |newspaper=The Journal News |access-date=December 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe MTA [[countersuit|countersued]] Rockefeller for the same amount, citing the cost of the damage resulting from the accident. In April 2019 the federal judge hearing the case dismissed the MTA's motion for [[summary judgement]], ruling that Rockefeller had presented enough evidence that a juror could reasonably conclude his former employer was at fault. The railroad had in response introduced evidence from the train's event recorder that suggested Rockefeller had been driving the train erratically earlier on that run, at one point slowing to less than {{cvt|50|mph}} on a section where the speed limit was around {{cvt|70|mph}}, and had told Herbert when the train left Poughkeepsie that \"it's your job to keep me awake\", an account Herbert had denied making to prosecutors from the Bronx D.A.'s office during their investigation.<ref name=\"Rockefeller lawsuit April 2018 story\" />{{efn|Herbert said that was ridiculous as she could not have prevented Rockefeller from suffering a medical emergency and held him blameless in the crash. Her lawsuit against the MTA over her injuries from the accident, in which she had made the same argument as Rockefeller, was settled for $835,000 in 2015.<ref name=\"2018 lawsuit followup story\" />}} Four months later, Rockefeller withdrew the suit.<ref name=\"Riverdale Press story\">{{cite news|last=Hinman|first=Michael|title=Spuyten Duyvil crash engineer drops lawsuit|url=https://www.riverdalepress.com/stories/spuyten-duyvil-crash-engineer-drops-lawsuit,69819?|newspaper=The Riverdale News|date=August 25, 2019|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Criminal investigation====\n\nThe office of [[Bronx District Attorney]] [[Robert Johnson]] reviewed the evidence gathered to see whether criminal charges, which could be as serious as [[negligent homicide]], were warranted against Rockefeller.<ref name=\"Rockland Times story\" /> While criminal charges have been filed against the operators of vehicles in other recent deadly transportation accidents in and around New York City, and convictions have often resulted, defense lawyers said in this case it would be difficult to find a credible offense, since Rockefeller was exhibiting no clear sign of negligence such as alcoholism or cell phone use, and operating a vehicle while drowsy is not necessarily a crime. [[World Wide Tours bus crash#Prosecution of Ophadell Williams|In 2012]], prosecutors argued that Ophadell Williams, the driver of a bus on which 15 passengers died on their way to a casino in [[Connecticut]], had knowingly endangered lives by repeatedly driving without adequate sleep. But the jury acquitted him of all charges except operating a vehicle without a [[driver's license|license]].<ref name=\"Prosecution possibilities story\" />\n\nIn May 2015, almost a year and a half after the accident, the Bronx D.A.'s office announced it would not be filing charges. \"There was no criminality in the act, therefore no criminal charges,\" said a spokeswoman for Johnson, adding that he had made that decision several months beforehand. Rockefeller's lawyer, Jeffrey Chartier, said that since his client hadn't known of his medical condition, he could not be considered to be negligent. It was \"the only logical conclusion\", similar to what the NTSB had already found.<ref name=\"Journal News no charges story\">{{cite news|last=Peltz|first=Jennifer|title=Bronx derailment: No charges for engineer in '13 crash|url=http://www.lohud.com/story/news/transit/2015/05/14/charges-engineer-william-rockefeller-caused-nyc-train-derailment-crash/27342575/|newspaper=[[The Journal News]]|date=May 15, 2015|accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nChartier said Rockefeller was still suffering from [[post-traumatic stress disorder]] (PTSD) as a result of the accident.<ref name=\"Journal News no charges story\" /> Smith, whose sister Donna died in the accident, accepted Johnson's decision, saying it spared her the stress of having to relive the accident at trial, stress [[2015 Philadelphia train derailment|a similar recent Amtrak accident]] was causing her at the time. She felt it was punishment enough for Rockefeller to have to live with his role in the accident. \"\"In a way, he's in jail forever, because he's got to live with this.\"<ref name=\"THR Linda Smith 2015 story\">{{cite news|last=Nani|first=James|title=Metro-North derailment victim's sister talks about decision not to criminally charge train's engineer|url=http://www.recordonline.com/article/20150515/NEWS/150519520/101008|newspaper=[[Times-Herald Record]]|date=May 16, 2015|accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Trains|New York City}}\n* [[List of American railroad accidents]]\n* [[List of rail accidents (2010\u2013present)]]\n\n===Similar accidents===\n* [[2015 Philadelphia train derailment]], later accident involving an Amtrak ''[[Northeast Regional]]'' train that sped in a 50&nbsp;mph curve more than twice that speed limit\n* [[2016 Hoboken train crash]], later accident involving New York City-area commuter rail where engineer was diagnosed with sleep apnea, possibly explaining why he lost awareness going into a station\n* [[2017 Washington train derailment]], also involving a train that went into a 30&nbsp;mph curve at more than twice that limit\n* [[Bourne End rail crash]], similar accident in Britain where a sleep-challenged engineer may have momentarily lost attention and taken the train into a curve too fast\n* [[Grantham rail crash]], another British accident with a similar momentary lapse of the engineer's attention suggested as an explanation for why he [[signal passed at danger|disregarded signals]] and derailed the train by taking it into a misaligned switch\n* [[Redondo Junction train wreck]], worst rail accident in Los Angeles history, where engineer who claimed to have \"blacked out\" before going into a curve too fast\n* [[Newton, Massachusetts, train collision]], in 2008, where the engineer's sleep apnea was also blamed posthumously for her inattention at a crucial moment\n* [[O'Hare station train crash]] in 2014; may also have been caused by an overworked, sleep-deprived train operator\n*[[2016 Croydon tram derailment]] a similar accident caused by a driver undergoing microsleep while in command of a tram.\n\n===Other Metro-North accidents===\n* [[Fairfield train crash]], May 2013\n* [[Valhalla train crash]], February 2015\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|December 2013 Spuyten Duyvil derailment}}\n* [http://app.ntsb.gov/investigations/2014/mnrsi/mnrsi.html#bronx2 Metro North Derailment - Bronx, NY] - NTSB\n* [http://app.ntsb.gov/doclib/reports/2014/RAB1412.pdf NTSB Railroad Accident Brief: Metro-North Railroad Derailment] - October 28, 2014\n\n{{2013 railway accidents}}\n\n[[Category:2013 in New York City]]\n[[Category:Derailments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving Metro-North Railroad]]\n[[Category:Railway accidents in 2013]]\n[[Category:Railway accidents and incidents in New York City]]\n[[Category:December 2013 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:21st century in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Spuyten Duyvil, Bronx]]\n", "name_user": "Daniel Case", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCriminal investigation:tighten. \"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/December_2013_Spuyten_Duyvil_derailment"}
